 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Mitchell Report published</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Mitchell Report published</b><br><br><br><b><h2>20 January 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Ulster peace may hinge on senator</h2><h3>Hopes of  an Irish settlement could soon crumble if the Mitchell commission's report on Wednesday gets it wrong  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Sharrock</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>John Bruton, the Irish prime minister, yesterday urged all parties, and his own and the British government, to accept the Mitchell  report on illegal weapons when it is published next Wednesday, nearly a week later than planned.  <p>  <p>Mr Bruton's plea was a recognition that not everybody will be happy with the report's findings, and that next week could be crucial  to a real peace in Northern Ireland, nearly 17 months after the IRA declared its ceasefire. Senator George Mitchell, President Clinton's  special envoy to Ireland, understands better than anyone that if he gets it wrong on Wednesday the peace process could soon unravel.  But he warned this week after meeting John Major at Downing Street that success is not guaranteed - saying "only the parties can break  the impasse".  <p>  <p>Mr Mitchell - assisted by General John de Chastelain, the Canadian chief of defence staff, and Harri Holkeri, ex-prime minister of  Finland - has impressed the parties from whom he has been taking submissions. "He asked incisive, perceptive questions," said one  participant in the commission's hearings.  <p>  <p>Mr Mitchell is further hampered in finding agreement among Northern Ireland's factions by the narrow remit to which he is working.  He has been asked, in effect, to square the circle which lies between the Government's insistence that the IRA gives up some arms  before talks begin, and Sinn Fein's insistence on no preconditions.  <p>  <p>Achieving this in isolation of the broader political picture seems impossible, which may be why Downing Street briefed journalists  last week that Mr Mitchell was looking at proposals first mooted by Ian Paisley, the Democratic Unionist Party leader, but more widely  promoted by Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble, for an election to a convention, assembly or 'body'. Mr Mitchell denied the  newspaper reports, saying this went beyond the boundaries of his task.  <p>  <p>However, the rumours that an election will take place have refused to go away, even after the leaders of Northern Irish nationalism  John Hume of the SDLP and Sinn Fein's Gerry Adams rejected the idea last weekend. Meanwhile Fianna Fail, the main Irish opposition  party, reportedly told Mr Mitchell there must be concessions to Sinn Fein or the IRA would go back to war. Mr Mitchell is alleged to  have said if this was the case, then it proved the unionists' case.  <p>  <p>So what can the 'three wise men' possibly devise to keep the peace process on course?  <p>  <p>The majority opinion is that it will serve up another portion of Ulster fudge, the diet which has kept the peace going for so long with  so little resolved. The problem is that the ground to be fudged has narrowed so greatly and the moment is fast approaching when hard  decisions can no longer be delayed.  <p>  <p>From the outset it has seemed highly unlikely Mr Mitchell will endorse the Government's demand for a token IRA arms surrender  before talks begin - even though a Belfast Telegraph opinion poll this week showed eight out of 10 people believed the paramilitaries  should hand over their weapons first. Mr Trimble has suggested an alternative road to the table via an election of some description, and  has accepted Sinn Fein's proposals for 'DIY' decommissioning. In order to keep Mr Trimble on board, the Mitchell commission may  conclude that if a weapons handover at this stage is unrealisable then the election proposal must be taken seriously. Mr Mitchell's  problem is then to convince Sinn Fein that they can live with this.  <p>  <p>For that reason there is fevered speculation about an 'electoral index' or 'party plebiscite', with participants in the all-party talks  submitting themselves to a poll to establish their respective levels of public support - or perhaps determine the number of  representatives each group is allowed. That kind of fudge would apparently satisfy both unionists and nationalists. However, that would  have done nothing about the issue Mr Mitchell was first invited to solve. It is understood that one paper he has been pointed towards  discusses a phased decommissioning, whereby all-party talks would first begin, but the paramilitaries would be expected to dispose of  their armaments in incremental steps. At what point the first 'payment' is made is of crucial importance and would require all Mr  Mitchell's cunning to resolve.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p><b>Who wants what</b>  <p>  <p>Dick Spring, Irish deputy prime minister:  <br>All-party talks as soon as possible. Believes paramilitaries must decommission, but no longer insists this must be before talks. Is  sceptical of "deeply flawed" Unionist proposals for elected assembly/convention.   <p>  <p>Ian Paisley, Democratic Unionist Party leader:  <br>Elected Ulster convention at which he is prepared to "shout" at Sinn Fein across the chamber. Vows never to negotiate with Sinn Fein.  Sees no role for Dublin in Northern Ireland.  <p>  <p>John Hume, SDLP leader:  <br>All-party talks without further delay. Says decommissioning of paramilitary weapons has already taken place; the guns will only  bark again if there is no progress. Opposed in public to Unionist proposals for new assembly, believing it is intended to thwart all-Ireland  dimension in any future settlement.  <p>  <p>Sir Patrick Mayhew, Northern Ireland Secretary:  <br>Publicly insists the IRA and loyalists must hand in some weapons before talks, but in private is prepared to accept whatever  proposals will ensure that Unionists will talk to Sinn Fein. Interested in an assembly if it will bring David Trimble along.  <p>  <p>Gerry Adams, Sinn Fein president:  <br>Rejects any IRA disarmament until a political settlement has been agreed, ie at the end of the process. His party accepts the principle  of decommissioning, saying the IRA might destroy weapons and permit independent verification. Rejects unionist proposals for a new  assembly.   <p>  <P>David Ervine, leader of Progressive Unionist Party, political wing of the Ulster Volunteer Force:  <br>All-party talks with no preconditions on arms, but notes that loyalist paramilitaries have made a "no first strike" pledge and would  hand over weapons if the IRA did. Interested by idea of an elected assembly, if large enough to guarantee loyalist representation.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
