 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Ofsted report reveals nearly half schools in England are failing their pupils </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Ofsted report reveals nearly half schools in England are failing their pupils </b><br><br><br><b><h2>6 February 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Tough targets  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Gillian Shephard</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Yesterday's annual report by HM's Chief Inspector of Schools highlighted the best and worst aspects of what is happening in our classrooms. We should all be delighted that the report was able to identify 203 excellent, good or improving schools. But the report also shows that we have a long way to go. None of us can ignore its findings.  <p>  <p>Overall standards of pupil achievement need to be raised in half our primary schools, and two fifths of our secondary schools; one lesson in five at key stages 2 and 3 is unsatisfactory.  <p>  <p>The Government has put in place measures to raise standards and these are starting to have an effect. But I intend to do more. Ofsted will work to a new and sharper-focused inspection framework from this April and inspectors will report to the head where they find examples of excellent or very poor teaching. Inspectors will give special attention to weak schools, and revisit them. The Teacher Training Agency is working to improve the quality of initial teacher training, drawing on Ofsted inspection reports that are now being published, and defining national priorities for in-service training.  <p>  <p>One of our top priorities has to be the concern about literacy and numeracy among primary pupils. That is why we will be setting up 20 literacy and numeracy centres to improve teaching. That means setting clear and ambitious targets and choosing the most effective teaching methods to deliver them. We shall introduce baseline assessment of pupils at five and, in the longer term, we shall move towards the publication of value-added information. It has been announced that the testing and assessment arrangements will be refined; in particular, calculators will be banned from one of the maths tests for 11-year-olds this year, and we are looking at how mental arithmetic can be tested.  <p>  <p>The TTA, Ofsted and School Curriculum and Assessment Authority will organise a series of seminars in March on improving the quality of teaching. These are some of the things the Government is doing. But schools, heads, teachers, governors, LEAs and teacher trainers are also involved. Schools should set targets for their own improvement. Heads carry the responsibility for leading their schools to meet these targets. Teachers have to deliver them. The messages in the report are ones which every teacher should think long and hard about. Governors can ensure that their schools have a clear strategy for improvement. LEAs and teacher trainers can offer support services to schools to bring those improvements about. Parents need to be informed about how much progress is being made. The publication of performance tables for secondary schools has been a great success in giving that information to parents and in enabling schools to set their own targets. There was a high rate of participation in tests at 11 this year.  <p>  <p>The SCAA has carried out a thoroughgoing review of assessment and testing and made excellent proposals for changes to consolidate and strengthen the arrangements this year. So I have every confidence that the 1996 results will provide a solid basis for producing high quality performance tables for 11-year-olds, and my Department will be making the necessary preparations to enable us to do so.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
