 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Welfare spending to be slashed by a quarter</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Welfare spending to be slashed by a quarter</b><br><br><br><b><h2>7 February  1996</h2></b><br><h2>Clarke tries to square cuts and welfare  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Michael White</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The Chancellor, Kenneth Clarke, yesterday laid out his most trenchant defence yet of a fair but  efficient welfare state - free at the point of use - which Tory Britain will be able to finance  because of its growing economic success. He claimed it was possible to square the circle between New Right pressure for lower taxes and One  Nation Tory support for comprehensive health, education and welfare services, provided the  Government's commitment to "an enterprise economy" delivers the goods.  <p>  <p>In a speech which discreetly taunted Thatcherite MPs with the spectre of "riots on the streets" if  welfare cuts are made too quickly, the Chancellor insisted that he and John Major shared his own  declared objective "to reduce spending below 40 per cent of gross domestic product (GDP)". After weeks  in which he has been accused of dragging his heels against radical demands for far deeper cuts - and a  GNP share of 35 per cent or less on US or Asian lines - he said: "There is no limit that need be set  at this stage on how far further down this road we will go."  <p>  <p>Despite his reputation as what Labour's Chris Smith dubbed the Cabinet's "last One Nation Tory" Mr  Clarke's speech at the London School of Economics's Centre for Economic Performance yesterday was not  intended to pick a fight with the right. He brushed aside claims of splits and suggestions that he is  being marginalised, and even praised the drive by Social Security Secretary, Peter Lilley, to trim  &#163;5bn a year off the &#163;80bn social security budget by 1999. Mr Clarke stressed: "Big  government is out - limited government is in."  <p>  <p>It prompted Mr Smith, shadow social security spokesman, to accuse Mr Clarke of "rewriting history"  in ignoring the degree of job and home insecurity created by Tory policies. Since 1979 they had  doubled the number of people dependent on the state from one in 12 to one in six, Mr Smith said. But  the Chancellor was unrepentent in making his familiar Middle England appeal that flexible, free market  economics require "fewer snakes and more ladders" for families wanting to make a decent living.  <p>  <p>"People need to be reassured more than ever before that, through thick and thin, their health will  be looked after, their children educated, and a safety net provided for their old age and periods of  involuntary unemployment. In this way a strong welfare state can complement, not hinder, more flexible  markets by reducing fear of change and opposition to it," he said.  <p>  <p>At the same time he warned that the welfare state could not be allowed to expand "unimpeded" or at  the pace it had in the Seventies. Then public spending's share of GDP peaked at 47.25 per cent, compared  with 45.5 per cent at the peak of the early Eighties recession, 43.5 per cent in the Nineties recession and 42  per cent this year. The trend was now down, he insisted: "Our aim is to leave our children a welfare system which works  and which they can afford."  <p>  <p>But to avoid the welfare network becoming "unaffordable and inadequate at the same time" it was  imperative to contain spending on social security, health and education, the former health and  education secretary said. Rightwingers will not be appeased by what amounts to a defence of the status  quo, while Labour is flirting with radical reforms of its own. Mr Smith praised the Chancellor's  "laudable" wish to retain a strong welfare system even if government policies had tripled income  support costs to over &#163;16bn.  <p>  <p>"Instead of rewriting the past he would have been better employed looking at how we can build a  real welfare state for the future," he said.   <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
