 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year -  Immigration tribunal rules that Jayaram Khadka should be allowed to stay in GB </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Immigration tribunal says Jayaram Khadka should be allowed to stay in GB </b><br><br><br><b><h2>8  February 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Nepalese boy 'can stay with millionaire'  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>John Mullin</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>A Nepalese boy brought to Britain by a businessman who treated him as his son and made him heir to  his &#163;2.5m fortune should be allowed to stay, an immigration appeals tribunal said yesterday. It ruled there were exceptional  compassionate circumstances which allowed Jayaram Khadka, 19, to remain and strongly recommended that  a deportation order be rescinded.  <p>  <p>But the recommendation, following a hearing last month, carries no legal force, and Michael Howard,  the Home Secretary, is free to send him back to Nepal. Only in a minority of cases after a tribunal recommendation does the Home Secretary change his  mind, although a Home Office spokesman conceded the case was extremely unusual.  <p>  <p>Richard Morley, 42, a former naval officer who made his fortune from information technology,  brought Jayaram to Britain to fulfil a pledge he made to the boy's father in 1984. The father, a  policeman who suffered a heart condition, had run for three days to raise the alarm after Mr Morley  suffered a collapsed lung while climbing in the Himalayas.  <p>  <p>As a reward, Mr Morley agreed to look after his son should his illness overcome him, and brought  Jayaram, virtually destitute, to Britain in 1990 following his father's death two years earlier.  <p>  <p>But there was a mix-up over his age, and Jayaram entered the country on a passport which showed him  to be four years older than he was, and the Home Office has so far insisted that means he must be sent  back.  <p>  <p>Mr Morley, who has educated Jayaram at his home, yesterday repeated his pledge to leave Britain  with Jayaram should the Home Office deport him. Jayaram has lived at Clearwell Castle in the Forest of  Dean with Mr Morley in an unorthodox family relationship, with three other men, two women and another  boy. Mr Morley has rejected suggestions of any improper or homosexual relationships among the group,  who live together after contracting into what he calls The Family.  <p>  <p>The tribunal said they had been impressed by the evidence they had heard from family members,  including Ford exective Martin Jones, 31, and Helen Thomas, 40, Mr Morley's girlfriend. "We have no reason to think that any aspect of the community is other than that which was laid  before us, a community made up of persons who have decided they wish to live together and to commit  themselves to each other." The tribunal agreed with Mr Morley's argument that Jayaram had never been,  nor ever would be, a charge on public funds. "We were impressed by Mr Khadka's evidence and the way he gave it. We think that the life he would  live in Nepal, having had the experience of the family life he has had in this country, would be  traumatic for him."   <p>  <p>Mr Morley said: "It has been a great victory for justice, but there is still  concern over whether the Government will follow the recommendations." Jayaram said: "To have to leave  suddenly and go to a place where people might not understand me would be a very traumatic time for me.  I would be isolated from my family and people whom I trust 100 per cent." The Home Office said it  would study the ruling.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
