 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - US makes bid in nuclear sell-off</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>US makes bid in nuclear sell-off</b><br><br><br><b><h2>10 February 1996</h2></b><br><h2>MPs damn nuclear sell-off</h2><h3>Proceeds could be less than 2.9bn cost of Sizewell B - Cut-price offer to finance tax cuts feared  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Chris Barrie</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>MPs are to demand that the Government withdraw the country's newest nuclear power station, Sizewell B, from the controversial nuclear privatisation this summer for fear that the sell-off of the industry will raise less than it cost to build this one &#163;2.9bn reactor.  <p>  <p>The recommendation is included in a draft report by the Commons Trade and Industry Select Committee, a copy of which has been seen by the Guardian. The devastating report expresses concern that the Government is rushing into a cut-price privatisation and may squander the proceeds on tax cuts. It comes as ministers are in final talks with the industry over the financial structure of the sale, expected to raise no more than &#163;2.5bn. The draft also calls into serious question many of the Government's assumptions about the financing of the industry's multi-billion bill for cleaning up stations and dealing with nuclear waste.  <p>  <p>The Government, and particularly Michael Heseltine, the Deputy Prime Minister, comes under direct fire for misleading the public over the privatisation plans.  <p>  <p>Mr Heseltine pledged that the sell-off would lead to an eight per cent cut in electricity bills but the committee reckons that the savings are more likely to be 5 per cent because the nuclear levy - a surcharge on all electricity bills - will not expire this year as the Deputy Prime Minister promised. It also warns that the Government's decision to make no special provision for funding the clean-up of elderly Magnox reactors, which are to remain state-owned, could threaten other public sector investments, like schools and hospitals, when the nuclear bill falls due.  <p>  <p>MPs were due to publish their findings next Wednesday, but the financial complexities of the Government's second attempt to sell off nuclear power may delay publication until nearer the end of the month.  <p>  <p>The final shape of the report could yet be altered in last-minute haggling by MPs on the influential backbench committee, and there is still thought to be a chance that they will fail to agree a unanimous stance. Twelve days ago Ian Lang, the trade and industry secretary, rejected a suggestion from his Labour shadow, Margaret Beckett, that the sell-off be suspended until the committee had issued its report. Among the report's most sensitive conclusions are that Sizewell B, the most modern atomic station with only nine months' operating experience, be withdrawn from the sale, kept in state hands, and run under licence by British Energy.  <p>  <p>The draft says that it would be "unsatisfactory" if the reactor were sold for significantly less than its value in order to achieve a sale by a particular date.  <p>  <p>Although the Government has set up plans for a special ring-fenced fund to save up cash to pay for the decommissioning of those reactors being privatised and dealing with their fuel, the MPs suggest the fund may not cover all the &#163;10.5bn costs.  <p>  <p>The report says that the uncovered costs could render the privatised reactors uneconomic, and in such an event the liabilities would fall on the future taxpayers. The MPs want the fund to be extended, or sensitive fuel reprocessing contracts to be renegotiated.  <p>  <p>The report calls on the Government to reverse its policy of refusing to establish a similar segregated fund to cover a further &#163;14.3bn of clean-up costs for the Magnox reactors.  <p>  <p>Without such a guarantee, money for decommissioning could be spent on tax cuts or diverted to other public spending needs such as schools and hospitals.  <p>  <p>MPs are particularly alarmed that the Government is pressing ahead with the sell-off without having put in place a strategy for dealing with radioactive waste.  <p>  <p>The cost of its tentative proposals to to build a dump at Sellafield in Cumbria were uncertain and, were they to collapse, the likelihood would be that the bill would rise sharply. The report believes this could be biggest area of risk for potential investors.  <p>  <p>Ministers are also criticised for claiming that they could cut the clean-up costs of the old Magnox reactors by &#163;900m.  <p>  <p>The report says there is no evidence that this was "anything more than an informed guess". The committee insists that all liabilities - including a &#163;4bn bill for reprocessing fuel already used by reactors -  <p>  <p>should be made the responsibility of the new private company and not the taxpayer.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
