 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Hall Sporting</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Scott Inquiry report published</b><br><br><br><b><h2>16 February 1996</h2></b><br><h2>The Scott  Report - Unsound advice and inadequate briefings</h2><h3>Report reserves some of its harshest strictures for  the civil servants</h2>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Clare Dyer</b><br><br>      Sir Brian Unwin, head of Customs and Excise, told the inquiry he decided to pursue the case despite  being given "storm signals" by senior civil servants. They hinted that he would be entering "highly  delicate territory". Sir Richard accepts the decision to prosecute was made independently of  government ministers, who would have preferred to let the matter drop. But Customs and Excise is  critised for adopting a stance too closely aligned to the Government.  <p>  <p>The report notes that on 6 November 1992, a day after Alan Clark completed the evidence that led to  the trial's collapse, Sir Brian called a meeting with Alan Moses QC, Customs' senior prosecuting  counsel, to discuss dropping charges against the defendants. Mr Moses told the meeting that Customs  had executed the policy of clamping down on companies suspected of exporting arms to Iraq "in its role  as enforcement agents for the Government's export licence policy".  <p>  <p>Mr Moses comes in for criticism over his application to trial judge Brian Sweeney to have  information withheld from the defence under PII certificates. These "gagging orders" were signed by  five government ministers. Mr Moses said in pre-trial hearings that he had read the documents which the Government wished to  keep secret. He concluded they did not assist the defence "in relation to any foreseeable issue".  <p>  <p>But Sir Richard calls Mr Moses's advice "fundamentally unsound" and "flawed". He continues: "The  value of the documents to the defendants in preparing to cross-examine government officials and  ministers . . . seems to me so obvious as to be hardly worth stating."  <p>  <p>But the report says Mr Moses was inadequately briefed by Customs. It blames Andrew Leithead, an  assistant Treasury Solicitor in charge of litigation for the Department of Trade and Industry.  <p>  <p>Mr Leithead played a key role in briefing Mr Moses to resist disclosure of the documents covered by  PII certificates. Sir Richard criticises the instructions as "inadequate". They omitted to mention  Michael Heseltine's reluctance to sign his certificate. Mr Heseltine had asked that his misgivings be  passed on to the judge.  <p>  <p>Mr Leithead is also criticised for advising two DTI officials to alter their witness statements.  Sentences in the statement by Anthony Steadman, head of the DTI's export licensing bureau at the time,  showing the department suspected the machine tools were being used for military purposes, were  deleted. Mr Leithead said in evidence that he was "merely suggesting to Mr Steadman what the correct  position would be".  <p>  <p>The report says: "It is clear that... Mr Leithead had no knowledge of the facts and matters with  which the statement was dealing... I do not doubt Mr Leithead's good intentions but it was, in the  circumstances, dangerous for him to take it upon himself to suggest alterations to the statement." Mr  Steadman is said to have misled, perhaps inadvertently, officials at the Foreign Office and Ministry  of Defence. His role centres on confusion over three 1988 export licences for machine tools. The end  use for the equipment was never established.  <p>  <p>But Eric Beston, a civil servant at the DTI export licensing bureau, is attacked over his evidence  at the trial. Sir Richard says his evidence "was not frank", and was designed to protect officials and  ministers. Sir Richard records Mr Beston's comments on his report's conclusions. "In retrospect, I  should have given more time to re-examining events and re-reading original papers. But it was never my  intention to give anything other than frank evidence."  <p>  <p>The report largely exonerates the ministers who signed the PII certificates. Malcolm Rifkind, then  defence secretary, unlike colleague Peter Lilley, then a minister at the Department of Trade and  Industry, at least read the information on which the certificates were based. He told the inquiry that  he "did not regard himself as having a discretion to decline to claim PII for documents which fell  within the 'advice to ministers' class." Mr Lilley was worried he might compromise security.  <p>  <p>Kenneth Clarke, then home secretary, gave permission for a Security Service officer to give  evidence anonymously, a decision which conflicted with the Attorney General's assertion that ministers  were under a duty to assert PII. The purpose was to rebut the defence that the Government knew of the  activities of Paul Henderson, of Matrix Churchill.  <p>  <p>Sir Richard says: "A witness statement of an intelligence officer was prepared and served on the  defence, without ministerial or judicial approval, because it suited the prosecution and  notwithstanding the fact that the contents of the statement fell within a class of information the  disclosure of which would, according to the responsible minister, be contrary to the public interest."  <p>  <p>Michael Heseltine, then trade and industry secretary, is exonerated for his role in signing a PII  certificate, and Sir Richard records his doubts over the need for the certificate.  <p>  <p>As foreign secretary, Sir Geoffrey (now Lord) Howe gave his name to the Howe guidelines on arms  trade with foreign countries. These were the guidelines the Government was accused of changing without  informing Parliament, relaxing controls on trade with Iraq.  <p>  <p>Along with Mr Waldegrave, he sent letters to MPs assuring them the policy had not changed. Sir  Richard says: "The statement in the letters that 'The Government have not changed their policy on  defence sales to Iraq or Iran' was untrue." Lord Howe had not been informed of junior ministers'  (including William Waldegrave's) agreement on the new formulation. But he knew that a broad relaxation  of policy had been agreed.  <p>  <p>Lady Thatcher, prime minister until 1990, told the enquiry she was in charge of policy, not  administration: "I was on the big issue." The report gives her a clean bill of health, saying she was  not kept informed. Sir Richard found explanations by Lord Howe and Mr Waldegrave about the absence of  communication to the prime minister "unconvincing".  <p>  <p>Some of the most daming criticism is saved for Rob Young, now one of the three top civil servants  in the Foreign Office. He recommended rejection of a request from David Steel, then the Liberal  Democrats' foreign affairs spokesman, for a list of exports to Iran and Iraq. Mr Young was head of the  Foreign Office's Middle East Department between 1987 and 1990. Mr Young argued that "to publish a list  would expose the Government to further pressure both at home and abroad." Sir Richard says: "The  avoidance of domestic criticism is... an unacceptable reason for witholding from Parliament  information about the activities of government."  <p>  <p>Mr Young is also criticised for providing what Sir Richard calls an "incomplete and misleading"  parliamentary answer for Foreign Office minister Lord Glenarthur in April 1989. Sir Richard's comments  are ambiguous: "I accept the sincerity of Mr Young's perception that there was 'no change in policy'  but I do not accept that his perception was correct or that his analysis of the result of what was  done and agreed in the period September 1988 to April/May 1989 is accurate."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
