 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year -  Greenwich wins battle to stage Millenium Exhibition in year 2000 </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b> Greenwich wins battle to stage Millenium Exhibition in year 2000 </b><br><br><br><b><h2>24 February 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Greenwich wins Millennium battle</h2><h3>Birmingham calls foul as commission picks London riverside site for celebration exhibition  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Maev Kennedy</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Greenwich has beaten off a challenge from Birmingham to stage the Millennium Exhibition in 2000 with a &#163;700m proposal involving a two-year exhibition with pavilions contributed by cities throughout the country, according to the Corporation of London.  <p>  <p>Michael Cassidy, policy chairman for the corporation, said yesterday that the Environment Secretary, John Gummer, had confirmed to him that the Millennium Commission had chosen London over the National Exhibition Centre in Birmingham.  <p>  <p>The commission is chaired by the Heritage Secretary, Virginia Bottomley, and includes the Deputy Prime Minister, Michael Heseltine, who is known to have favoured a London site as part of his cherished project to regenerate the East End and the Thames corridor.  <p>  <p>However a commission spokeswoman insisted yesterday that the final decision had not been made, and added: "We still hope to announce the site next week."  <p>  <p>Reports that six cities will hold linked exhibition projects were also premature, she said. Once the main site is announced the festival programme will be decided, and applications from the regions for grants invited. The leader of the Greenwich bid, Sir Bob Scott, was cautious. "The signs are that it is good news for Greenwich, but we are not throwing our hats in the air until we hear it officially."  <p>  <p>Unofficially, the NEC has been preparing for the worst since the chosen operator, the design consultancy Imagination, which preferred the NEC site, was asked to draw up equally detailed plans for the Greenwich peninsula site.  <p>  <p>The Millennium Commission will provide a grant of up to &#163;100m towards the exhibition, which is to open on New Year's Day 2000, and is expected to attract up to 30 million visitors. The value of the exhibition to Birmingham or London is calculated at &#163;700m.  <p>  <p>The NEC was prepared to invest &#163;50m in the project. When the London backers realised how close they had come to losing it, a massive effort, led by Mr Cassidy, was put into lining up support.  <p>  <p>The commission's decision angered Birmingham council. "It has been rigged," said the council leader, Theresa Stewart. "All the balls in this particular lottery were marked Greenwich."  <p>  <p>Anne Underwood, council Tory group leader, said: "It appears to confirm our worst fears that London was going to get it no matter how much better rival bids were."  <p>  <p>The Greenwich Meridian, much trumpeted in the bid, just nicks the corner of the site, which is downstream of the historic heart of Greenwich. Stratford East, one of the original four shortlisted sites, claims that it is actually closer to the Greenwich Observatory and the Cutty Sark.  <p>  <p>Greenwich says it is uniquely qualified to host the Millennium celebrations, which aim to rival the Great Exhibition in 1851 and the Festival of Britain in 1951.  <p>  <p>It is the point from which time and distance are measured - in Greenwich Mean Time and the Meridian - and offers a backdrop of historic monuments including Inigo Jones's Queen's House, the Royal Naval College, the National Maritime Museum, and the Cutty Sark.  <p>  <p>Mr Cassidy rejected criticisms that Greenwich was difficult to reach. The Jubilee Line Underground extension, due to be finished in 1998, would pass through the site bringing visitors from central London and Stratford, north of the river, where there would be a huge car park.  <p>  <p>"It's going to have the most modern railway in Britain, with the capability of moving 250,000 people a day."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
