 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Justice Taylor criticises Howard over mandatory life sentences </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Justice Taylor criticises Howard over mandatory life sentences </b><br><br><br><b><h2>6 March 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Seeking justice</h2><h3>Lord Chief Justice Taylor has crossed swords with Michael Howard but the main battle is yet to come  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Mary Riddell</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>When Lord Taylor of Gosforth announced his intention, some time ago, to appear on 'Question Time', his decision reduced one venerable columnist to a state of near-apoplexy. What inappropriate subjects, he hazarded, might the Lord Chief Justice be called upon to discuss? Trivia? Gossip? Or (this in a wild lunge for the most improbable topic he could think of) Virginia Bottomley's knickers?  <p>  <p>Lord Taylor is the unstuffiest of men and able, therefore, to laugh at this bizarre suggestion. "Yes, he did mention those. He was writing off the top of his head, of course, since I was only going to comment on legal matters." Which brings us safely back to a more familiar set of political underpinnings: Michael Howard's bloomers.  <p>  <p>Five months have elapsed since the Home Secretary announced to an adulatory conference his package of tougher sentences, reduced remission and automatic life terms for second-time serious sex offenders. The cheers had scarcely died before Taylor moved in for the kill.  <p>  <p>Judges' discretion must not be limited, he said, in the most devastating tirade in legal history. Why not, instead, supply the police with sufficient money to catch criminals? And then, his verdict delivered, he stayed silent. The row has smoked on ever since, but Taylor - driven into an unscripted role as defender of the public interest - has added not a further word. And now round two is imminent. Within the next few weeks Howard - this time possibly with the nervousness appropriate to a second-time offender - will produce the white paper detailing his plans. The battle lines are drawn, and Taylor is waiting.  <p>  <p>"The proposals were so, er, striking (he is a master of the understated adjective) that I thought I should indicate my disagreement with some of them at an early stage... I would like to see what the white paper says. It may be that it will be modified somewhat and therefore one doesn't want to beat the air."  <p>  <p>Since the notion of a climbdown by Howard is as probable as a certified sighting of the tooth fairy, it would seem the Lord Chief Justice is erring on the optimistic side here. "Well, if that is so, we shall have to meet it. If the proposals are as they have been signalled, then I shall oppose them, give reasons why, and speak against them in the House of Lords." Today he gives a lecture at King's College, London, and those close to him expect it to contain the first public salvo on sentencing policy. Taylor, the most unexcitable of men, will have measured his text carefully. His appearance - pin-stripes, watch chain and grey silk hanky tucked into a top pocket - suggests an urbanity untinged with pugilism. Do not be deluded, for his plan of campaign represents a preview of the most cataclysmic dust-up yet in the fractured relationship between government and judiciary. If there were grounds for reconciliation, Taylor would take them, but he sees none. "I am certainly not in favour of the two central proposals of mandatory life sentences for two or more serious sexual offences, and minimum sentences. That is not because it's curbing our power - there is no question of amour propre - but because it restricts the scope for doing justice."  <p>  <p>There is no question of amour of any variety in the current chilly climate of mistrust. While Taylor has been staying tactfully silent, his colleagues have not. Lord Hailsham has viewed the Home Secretary's plans with "very grave suspicion", Lord Donaldson has warned of "government by despots", and Lord Justice Rose has said that violent criminals may, if Howard has his way, murder their victims rather than stopping at assault.  <p>  <p>Such views, according to Taylor, are normally run past him before being aired. Since he recommends a toning down of anything over-political, one wonders quite what bombshells may lurk in the wastebins of the Royal Courts of Justice. But does he agree with his colleagues? "Well, I do think there's a risk that if someone rapes a little girl and has done so on a previous occasion and knows that he will get a life sentence if convicted, he may very well feel like removing the only witness who can identify him and say what happened. That's a very real risk.  <p>  <p>"I also think there's a need for discounts to be allowed on pleas of guilty. If you're going to have mandatory life sentences, that factor goes. So you'll get nobody pleading guilty to a second rape."  <p>  <p>Let us pause here, look back and wonder, as Taylor must, how we ever reached such dire straits. When he took over four years ago as Britain's top judge, via a glittering career at the Bar (he prosecuted both Jeremy Thorpe and John Poulson), the Hillsborough soccer disaster report and a fast-track rise through the judicial ranks, the system he inherited appeared formalin-bottled.  <p>  <p>Here was a judiciary which, according to legend, had not yet heard of the Beatles. "Oh, that old thing... I think judges are reasonably au fait now. One's children and grandchildren (he has four of each) keep you in touch. I know about Mr Blobby and Wallace and, er, Grommit." Taylor, in his own description "user-friendly", was to be the great force for modernisation. The first thing he did, on his appointment, was to hold a press conference. Since his predecessor, Lord Lane, would have been as likely to throw a garage house party, this was seen as the boldest of moves, a litmus test of the new openness bolstered by the Lord Chancellor's move to give judges the freedom to speak out.  <p>  <p>In Taylor's view, there is still some way to go. "If a particular decision doesn't please, the temptation is to to say: Here's a fusty old judge wearing a horsehair on his head, went to Oxbridge, all those awful things... although why it should be awful to go to a decent university (he is a graduate of Pembroke) I don't know. Anyway, that approach still comes up. I'm disappointed things haven't moved further. But the pendulum may have swung too far for some. There are those who say the judges are getting above themselves." And are they? "I don't think so. I absolutely don't. You need the judiciary to see that people don't transgress their powers." Step once more into the frame, Michael Howard, large numbers of whose decisions (although, as Taylor is at pains to point out, by no means all) have been overturned by a judiciary composed, some would say, of perilously liberal muesli-eaters.  <p>  <p>"Yes, they even ride bicycles, so help me," says Taylor in his only reference to Sir Richard Scott, whose report findings he presaged long ago when he cited the Government's abuse of justice in the first arms-to-Iraq trial. Specifics apart, Taylor and his Alpen-crunchers have achieved much. He is particularly pleased that the waiting time for appeals has been reduced, that more judges have been hired, that litigation is swifter, if still too expensive, for "the little man" - his target audience for all reforms.  <p>  <p>It was naturally never part of the grand plan that the judiciary would be thrown into open warfare with the Government. Indeed, Taylor abhors judicial involvement in politics and extraneous criticisms of ministers. Nonetheless the scene was set for divergence on a range of issues. The decision last week by the European Court of Human Rights to remove the Home Secretary's powers to decide on the release of young murderers re-evoked once again the Bulger case and the disparity over the sentencing of Jon Venables and Robert Thompson.  <p>  <p>The trial judge said eight years. Taylor revised that to 10 and the Home Secretary stipulated 15. "We have to recommend what would be appropriate for retribution and deterrence. Clearly an awful case, but one would scale down the period bearing in mind the age of the offenders. But the Home Secretary has other considerations, such as the impact on the public. I don't think I can comment further."  <p>  <p>His wish is that the European Convention on Human Rights should be incorporated into British law - an institution he wants to see otherwise less tampered with. "There has been a great deal of government interference - please make that activity - in the way we live. We've had more criminal justice acts in the last few years than in the previous 60." And none of them much good? "No. They come too fast, and they're done on the hoof." It is that, perhaps, which most preoccupies the Lord Chief Justice, as he rises early to read endless legal papers and snatches a few moments a day to practise the piano he plays to near-professional standards. ("I only do charity concerts now, so that if something goes wrong no one can demand their money back.")  <p>  <p>The great moderniser had planned for progress, but it is clear that he believes the Government has instead decreed a shambles. "In the last three years, almost everything has been changed or thrown overboard in the criminal justice system. When you are going to legislate, you should do it less hectically and with a little more preparation and not have to introduce amendments because you hadn't got them ready before."  <p>  <p>Hectic seems a very polite word to apply to the Home Secretary's Criminal Justice Bill. "I used it carefully," says Taylor, with a most charming smile. "I won't go further."  <p>  <p>Oh, but he will. As Howard may dismally reflect, while toiling over his forthcoming white paper, he most certainly will.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
