 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Bioethics panel approves heart transplants from pigs to humans  </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Bioethics panel approves heart transplants from pigs to humans  </b><br><br><br><b><h2>7 March 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Pig heart swaps to humans approved  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Tim Radford</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>A panel of leading scientists has given a cautious go-ahead for heart transplants from genetically-altered pigs to humans.  But the approval from the Nuffield Council on Bioethics, announced yesterday, could actually slow progress in the new science of xenotransplantation. <p><p>The scientists are asking for reassurance that no new diseases could be introduced into the human population along with animal organs.  They urge that there should be no human trials until the Government's own committee on xenotransplantation has approved procedures.  <p>  <p>The council's examination of the ethical problems that science now poses comes after an announcement last September by a Cambridge biotechnology firm, Imutran Ltd, that the first clinical tests of pig-to-human heart transplants could happen in 1996.  <p>  <p>A heart surgeon at Papworth hospital and a Cambridge biologist have been working for years to produce a line of pigs with a genetic alteration which would make their hearts immunologically acceptable to human patients. Pig hearts have much the same pumping power as human hearts: chimpanzees are more closely related to humans but would take longer to breed for surgery, and there are conservation objections.  <p>  <p>Albert Weale, professor of government at the University of Essex and chairman of the Nuffield Council's working party which reported yesterday, pointed out that society dined on pigs, and that pig heart valves were already used in transplant surgery.  "Around 5,000 patients are on the waiting list for transplants but because of the shortage of donated human organs fewer than 3,000 human organ transplants were performed in 1995."  But the problem of rejection - the most difficult aspect of a transplant operation - had still to be resolved. There was concern for animal rights, along with possible religious and emotional objections.  <p>  <p>And the working party wanted to be convinced that no new and serious disease - no unknown virus lurking in the pigs - would be introduced to humans. "Our view was that the benefits of transplantation are so considerable, and the present organ shortage so serious, that it would be ethically acceptable to develop xenotransplantation experimentally, in order to explore its potential for solving the problem of organ shortage." Because pigs were more distantly related to humans than baboons or chimpanzees, the chance of a transfer of infection across the species boundary was much lower, and the risk almost impossible to assess.  Because of this, safeguards might be harder to demonstrate.  <p>  <p>David Morton, professor of biomedical science and ethics at the University of Birmingham, saw no problems with genetic alteration. Species boundaries were not inviolate; evolution demonstrated that.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
