 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - David Ashby deselected by local party</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Ashby deselected by local party</b><br><br><br><b><h2>9 March 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Tories ditch MP who lost gay libel case  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Helen Nowicka</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>David Ashby, the Conservative MP who lost a libel action three months ago over allegations that he was a homosexual, was last night deselected by his constituency party.  <p>  <p>Mr Ashby has represented the marginal seat of Leicestershire North West since 1983, winning with a slender majority of 979 at the last election. After hearing him argue his case, more than 200 members of the constituency party voted in a secret ballot not to readopt him. Members of the association's executive committee had publicly urged him to offer his resignation before the meeting.  <p>  <p>Afterwards Mr Ashby said: "I am absolutely certain I am the only person who could win this seat, but being in public life has been very difficult indeed... I must admit I am rather delighted to be out of it." He added that he may consider applying to be selected for another seat.  <p>  <p>Clifford McKee, the association chairman, said work would begin immediately to select a new candidate.  <p>  <p>Local Tories were concerned that Mr Ashby, aged 55, became a household name during his libel case against the Sunday Times. The paper had claimed he was having an affair with a man later identified as Irish doctor Ciaran Kilduff. Mr Ashby denies he is homosexual. Star witness for the paper was the MP's wife, Silvana, who claimed her husband had told her he was homosexual when their 28-year marriage ended.  <p>  <p>On Wednesday Mr Ashby angered his constituency by voting with Labour to defeat the Government on part of the Housing Bill. The clause gives homosexual couples the same right to stay in a council or housing association property as married people if the partner who officially holds the tenancy dies.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALI