 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Rock climbers secure tree positions in 'Battle of Newbury'</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Rock climbers secure tree positions in 'Battle of Newbury'</b><br><br><br><b><h2>25 March 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Barking up the right tree</h2><h3>Why are the authorities trying to massage the news coverage of Newbury?  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>John Vidal</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Oh dear. The Guardian has upset the Government's Highways Agency, the police and now the Under Sheriff of Berkshire. Reliance Security are not best friends either - but that's another story. The problem is the media 'arrangements' made for the 'Third Battle of Newbury'.  <p>  <p>Hostilities opened two weeks ago. I had spent the night with protesters 80 feet up a tree. Given the constant running fights, the self-evident illegal assaults, the acts of bravery and the punches being swapped between the protesters and bailiffs at every eviction from trees along the bypass route, 80 feet up was the only place to be when the law came knocking. It was important to be close to the action because the press and legal observers were being made - "for their own safety" - to stay well clear. The danger of trees uprooting themselves and flying several hundred yards on to journalists is as real in Newbury as people not being able to see what is going on in front of their eyes.  <p>  <p>The protesters, who felt that their situation was the most endangered, welcomed the Guardian's commitment to witness what was going on. So did the few bailiff's climbers with whom I managed to speak. Both 'sides' agreed that there should be independent observers of the evictions. Problems began when freelance journalist Jay Griffiths and I were spotted wearing climbing harnesses - a red rag to the Newbury authorities, who assume that anyone wearing one is an enemy of the state. From then on we were constantly harassed, firstly by the Central Office of Information, which acts as the lead agency for all Newbury information. A press officer physically obstructed us from getting into a press conference with the under sheriff, Nicholas Blandy, because we were not wearing British standard hard hats, the correct fluorescent jackets saying 'Press' front and back, or the right sort of identification, even though they knew perfectly well who we were and referred to us by name.  <p>  <p>Matters deteriorated after that. Blandy threatened to have us arrested under Section 10 of the Criminal Law Act 1977 if he found us in his 'shrivalture' - that is, anywhere near the bypass route. He said that the protesters had forfeited their rights to protection by law as they were the "authors of their own misfortune". He only agreed to give the Guardian an interview after I had complained very loudly during a broadcast to the BBC that he was giving.  <p>  <p>Next came a chief inspector who formally warned us in Blandy's presence that if he found us in the trees he would treat us exactly the same as the protesters. It continued with an unidentifiable Highways Agency man, who threatened me verbally for listening to his colleague being interviewed by Swiss Radio and then technically assaulted Griffiths.  <p>  <p>More hassle came from a policeman, who formally cautioned me for using abusive language. Any more? Yes. Brays detective agency, which is employed by the Highways Agency to collect information about anyone attending road protests, aggressively filmed both of us on video and other cameras over several days. Then a letter was sent from a senior COI man to another Guardian journalist threatening to withdraw the newspaper's 'privileges' if we didn't toe the line. It suggested that the rest of the Newbury press would also lose their privileges if I continued to flaunt their rules. The last straw came when the Highways Agency press officer refused to speak to me because he thought (correctly, though he did not know it) that I was seeking information about a serious accident that happened while I was up a tree, as it was being cleared of protesters. 'Privileges', it seemed, had been withdrawn. All this for trying to report from a tree.  <p>  <p>No harm done, but there are serious issues. Questions: why are the authorities trying to massage the news coverage of Newbury? What right has an Andover solicitor (Blandy) to dictate to the world's media what they should wear, how they should be identified and just what they should see when men in his pay are being accused of assault and worse? Why will Blandy not allow trained, independent legal observers and the press into his security cordon, especially when there is a growing catalogue of alleged human rights abuses and complaints against chainsaw operators, guards, climbers and others? Why is it impossible to interview protesters during or immediately after the eviction? How can the Central Office of Information and the Highways Agency, both government bodies, try to withold information and 'withdraw privileges', like some school monitor, from bona fide journalists?  <p>  <p>The Highways Agency argues that the rest of the media has accepted "as pure common sense" the "minor conditions" restricting the press from full and open access to the story. They say that they refused to talk to me not because I was in a tree, but because "I was in a tree inside a cordon". They assume ("not unreasonably") that the presence of an unaccompanied journalist within the working cordon would constitute an obstruction.  <p>  <p>I was beginning to think it was becoming personal. Then Radio 5 Live's Stop Press team turned up at Newbury. They, too, were refused entry to one of Blandy's intimate press conferences because they only had their BBC identification. Tut, tut. Must get the right jacket, boys.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
