 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Liggett tobacco group agrees to help smokers quit in US court settlement </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Liggett tobacco group agrees to help smokers quit in US court settlement </b><br><br><br><b><h2>14 March 1996</h2></b><br><h2>US tobacco firm to help smokers quit</h2><h3>On no smoking day, a tobacco firm in the US finds itself having to pay millions of dollars to help people give up smoking  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Ian Katz</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>A leading US tobacco firm will spend millions of dollars helping people to give up smoking as part of a ground-breaking settlement in a lawsuit brought by smokers who claimed that cigarette companies had deliberately sought to hook them on their products.  <p>  <p>In a volte-face, Liggett Group, America's fifth largest tobacco firm, broke ranks with the rest of the industry to offer a settlement of the suit brought on behalf of up to 50 million American smokers.  <p>  <p>Under the deal, the company will not admit liability for tobacco-related illnesses but will contribute five per cent of its pre-tax profits for the next 25 years to a nationwide programme to help smokers give up.  It will also pay $4m (&#163;2.6m), and a further proportion of its profits, to four states which are separately suing the tobacco firms, and has agreed to accept US government curbs on cigarette advertising and marketing.  <p>  <p>The settlement, which was expected to be formally announced yesterday, represents a significant breakthrough for America's dogged anti-smoking campaigners because no tobacco firm has yet paid a penny in a smoking-related lawsuit.  <p>  <p>"Why should we keep spending $10m (&#163;6.5m) a year on legal fees if there is a way to settle it," Bennett LeBow, the majority shareholder in Liggett's parent company, the Brooke Group, told the Wall Street Journal.  <p>  <p>In exchange for its concessions, Liggett will be dropped from the so-called Castano class action suit, in which a consortium of nearly 60 law firms has alleged that tobacco companies deliberately manipulated nicotine levels in cigarettes in order to hook smokers.  <p>  <p>Four of the five states suing tobacco firms for the cost of treating tobacco-related illnesses - Florida, Massachusetts, Mississippi and West Virginia - will also drop their suits against the company, which produces Chesterfield cigarettes as well as a number of discount brands. The company's move will infuriate the rest of the $45bn (&#163;30bn) industry, which has come under attack in recent years from the US Congress, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) and countless city and state legislatures, seemingly competing to pass the most draconian smoking bans.  <p>  <p>The industry's policy has been to fight every lawsuit, confident that it can muster more resources than any group of aggrieved smokers. But the army of lawyers behind the Castano suit managed for the first time to level the legal playing field.  The suit, brought against the five largest tobacco companies, claimed the firms and their lobbying body, the Tobacco Institute, deliberately concealed research which showed that nicotine was addictive.  <p>  <p>Industry watchers believe the Liggett settlement had less to do with corporate contrition than Mr LeBow's campaign to force a split between the food and tobacco operations of R J R Nabisco, in which he is also a major shareholder. The Nabisco management has insisted it cannot spin off its tobacco operations until smoking-related lawsuits against the company have been resolved. But the terms of the Liggett deal would allow it to accept a similar settlement by taking over the smaller cigarette company. The Liggett settlement, which must still be approved by a federal judge, does not require the company to pay anything to individual smokers. The firm had pre-tax profits of $11m (&#163;7.4m) last year.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
