 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - New scare as govt admit link between CJD deaths and eating BSE-infected meat </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>New scare as government admits link between CJD deaths and eating BSE-infected meat </b><br><br><br><b><h2>23 March 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Stores set to replace British beef with imports </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Sally Weale</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Supermarkets were last night preparing contingency plans in the face of a mass consumer boycott of British beef.  <p>  <p>As criticism grew of the Government's delay in providing advice on children's consumption of beef, the Co-op announced that in view of the BSE scare it was considering breaking a 150-year tradition of stocking exclusively British beef.  A spokesman said buyers were looking into the possibility of importing meat from Australia, New Zealand or South America to stock its 3,000 stores in the face of growing concern about the safety of domestic supplies. <p>  <p>"We will be looking at providing alternatives because we recognise that this problem will result in consumers switching to other products," the spokesman said.  "We are extremely critical of the way the Government has handled this announcement and the delay in providing clear advice about children and the consumption of beef. It's creating a great deal of confusion." <p>  <p>Yesterday most supermarket chains were insisting it was too early to measure the impact of the Government's announcement on a possible link between 'mad cow disease' and the human illness, CJD, but all are anticipating a sharp decline in sales and are considering buying beef from elsewhere, as well as increasing orders for alternatives like poultry, pork and lamb. <p>  <p>During the last BSE scare before Christmas, sales of beef at Co-op stores fell by up to 25 per cent. The impact of this week's announcement is likely to be more severe given the implications of the government statement. "We've just come away from a store and the cabinet was still full of beef. Everyone's going for pork or chicken for this weekend," the spokesman said. <p>  <p>None of the supermarkets approached said they were withdrawing British beef, but customer demand will determine how shops respond.  <p>  <p>Somerfield Stores said a slump in sales was already apparent in its 625 outlets, with shoppers opting instead for lamb, pork and poultry. A spokesman said the company was looking into Irish beef.  <p>  <p>Hundreds of customers have taken advantage of an offer to return beef they bought prior to the announcement in exchange for double its purchase value. <p>  <p>Tesco, which stocks beef from 18 different suppliers in the UK and Ireland and clearly marks country of origin on all its products, said it had not decided whether to buy beef from elsewhere.  Corporate affairs manager David Sawday said: "We are monitoring what our customers want. We will get a feel for that in the next couple of days. This is a new experience for all of us."  <p>  <p>Sainsbury's is putting up information notices in its 362 stores. It is also producing recipe cards providing alternative ideas of everyday meals without beef. "We are considering all options," a spokesman said.  <p>  <p>A Waitrose spokeswoman said the supermarket chain was bracing itself for a sharp drop in sales. Its beef supplies came from known and approved farms and was produced to the "highest standards of husbandry and safety". Customers are being provided with leaflets offering information, and every branch manager has been briefed to deal with inquiries.  <p>  <p>Asda is also looking into buying beef from elsewhere. Demand has dropped, with sales of turkey and pork up 18 per cent compared with last week. "We have been securing increased quantities of turkey, pork, chicken and lamb to cope with increased demand, though demand for beef sirloin has remained buoyant," a spokeswoman said.  <p>  <p>Marks & Spencer reported a drop in demand for beef, with customers opting for fish, chicken and lamb.  A spokeswoman said information leaflets were available in all stores, but the company was awaiting further announcements from the Government before taking further action.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
