 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Unabomber suspect, Theodore Kaczynskis held</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Unabomber suspect, Theodore Kaczynsk, held</b><br><br><br><b><h2>5 April  1996</h2></b><br><h2>Misfit's lonely downfall</h2><h3>FBI agents believe they have finally caught up with a  serial bomber  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Ian Katz</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>By yesterday morning the pieces were sliding into place like parts of a jigsaw. He was a brilliant  mathematician who abandoned academia for a hermit-like existence. He lived in a tiny, hand-built cabin  without electricity or running water. He spoke little and read voraciously. The description of  Theodore Kaczynski could hardly have matched the profile drawn up by the FBI any better. Long before  the former Berkeley professor, aged 53, was charged in a Montana courtroom with possessing an  unregistered firearm - specifically, components from which an explosive device could be assembled -  agents who had hunted a technophobic serial bomber for almost two decades were convinced they had the  Unabomber.  <p>  <p>Perhaps only in Montana, a tolerant haven for eccentrics and extremists such as the so-called  Freemen holed up in a ranch several miles to the east, could the intense, bearded recluse have failed  to arouse suspicion. So disdainful of motorised transport was he that he rode everywhere on an old  bicycle fitted with homemade snow tires.  <p>  <p>Mr Kaczynski's arrest as he resisted a search of his cabin by FBI agents on Wednesday appeared to  have ended one of the most expensive and humiliating manhunts in American history.  <p>  <p>Ever since a primitive bomb exploded at Northwestern University in May 1978 injuring a security  guard, an army of agents had criss-crossed the country, always seemingly a step behind the bomber  whose campaign cost the lives of three people and maimed 23 others.  <p>  <p>In one of his many letters to newspapers, the bomber even took the trouble to taunt his pursuers:  "It doesn't appear the FBI is going to catch us any time soon," he wrote. "The FBI is a joke."  <p>  <p>In the end, it was not the thousands of hours spent combing library records, questioning academics,  or visiting scrap metal yards that led investigators to Mr Kaczynski's cabin outside the tiny town of  Lincoln. The 18-year-old case was broken by a stroke of luck.  <p>  <p>According to law enforcement sources, members of Mr Kaczynski's family became suspicious two months  ago when clearing out their bungalow in Chicago. Among the suspect's effects, they found a collection  of writings uncannily similar to the 35,000-word 'manifesto' published by the Washington Post and New  York Times in September.  <p>  <p>Fearing the worst, Mr Kaczynski's brother contacted the FBI. A search of the family home turned up  more clues, but even after weeks of painstaking surveillance, investigators said they did not have  enough evidence to arrest the former academic. That changed when agents searched his cabin on  Wednesday. According to the New York Times, they found explosive materials and bomb-making equipment.  <p>  <p>As agents had long suspected of the bomber, Mr Kaczynski had once lived in Chicago, northern  California and Utah. The suspect was described as a broody loner who was all but self-sufficient. He  spoke in enigmatically incomplete sentences.  <p>  <p>The young Mr Kaczynski was remembered as distinctly unmemorable. He passed quickly through high  school, winning a scholarship to study mathematics at Harvard University, before moving to the  University of Michigan to study for a doctorate.  <p>  <p>It was the mid-Sixties, and the Michigan campus was a cradle of student radicalism. But Mr  Kaczynski was remembered more for his academic achievements. The suspect's prefered intellectual  terrain was the recondite area of so-called 'complex analysis'.  <p>  <p>George Pirnaian, a mathematics professor who taught him, said: "He was a very able, very serious  student and he solved a very difficult problem in his thesis."  <p>  <p>After earning his doctorate, Mr Kaczynski took a job as an acting assistant professor at the  University of California at Berkeley, another hotbed of leftwing activism. After teaching mathematics  for two years, he resigned for unknown reasons.  <p>  <p>His path after leaving academia is less clear. According to reports yesterday, he took a succession  of odd-jobs as he wandered round the country. For a period around 1990, agents believe he lived in a  remote Afghanistan village.  <p>  <p>With his bizarre Luddite credo and fiendish bomb-making skills, the Unabomber has surpassed the  most notorious serial bomber in American history, the so-called Mad Bomber, George Metesky, whose  pursuers grudgingly admitted their admiration for his intelligence and craftsmanship. Investigators  could have had little idea of the trail of terror that lay ahead when amateurish devices exploded at  two Illinois universities in 1978 and 1979. Agents began to suspect that they might be dealing with a  serial bomber in November 1979 when a device exploded in the hold of an American Airlines flight to  Washington, without causing injury. Because his targets had been linked with universities and  airlines, they dubbed the case 'Unabomb'.  <p>  <p>The bomber struck regularly in the early Eighties. In 1980, the United Airlines president, Percy Wood,  was injured opening a package at his Chicago home. A Berkeley professor received one two years later.  In 1985, two people were maimed at the University of Michigan. Later that year, the bomber killed for  the first time. His victim was Hugh Scrutton, the owner of a computer store in Sacramento, California.  <p>  <p>The bomber appeared to have broadened his range of targets, but investigators still saw a pattern:  individuals linked with technology - in particular computers. They speculated Unabomber may have lost  his job to a computer.  <p>  <p>But the bombs themselves were a window on the Unabomber's personality, crafted from everyday items  such as scrap wood and lamp wire. Metal parts appeared to have been polished, and some even numbered.  <p>  <p>"He's doing these things not because he has to, but because he enjoys it or feels a compulsion to  do it," a retired FBI bomb expert who helped hunt the Unabomber for 14 years said. "I picture someone  bent over a bench late at night tinkering with the things. He may even be talking to himself while he  makes them."  <p>  <p>Frequently investigators manage to track down bombers through the rare components used in their  devices, but the Unabomber made everything himself. The agents hunting him with increasing desperation  got their first breakthough in 1987, when a man in a hooded sweatshirt and sunglasses was spotted  leaving what later proved to be a bomb in a Salt Lake City car park. They now had a sketch of their  suspect, but the bomber simply disappeared, stopping his attacks for six years.  <p>  <p>By the time a San Francisco geneticist was injured by one of his devices in June 1993, agents  conceded privately that their sketch was all but obsolete. The Unabomber resumed his campaign in  December 1994, mailing a bomb that killed an advertising executive, Thomas Mosser, in New Jersey. Four  months later, another device killed Gilbert Murray, head of a lobbying company which had worked for  the timber trade.  <p>  <p>The killing fuelled speculation about one aspect of the case. The Unabomber appeared to have a  fascination for wood: almost all his devices had some wooden parts.  <p>  <p>In April 1995, the Unabomber wrote to the New York Times declaring that he was an anarchist. He  announced that he was "getting tired of making bombs" and proposed a Faustian bargain: if the New York  Times and Washington Post would publish his 35,000-word manifesto, he would stop.  <p>  <p>The rambling diatribe eventually published by the Washington Post provided investigators with a  treasure trove of clues. In his rant, the bomber cited a small library of abstruse texts. Agents  combed university library lists to find out who had borrowed titles such as 'Chinese Political Thought  in the 20th Century'.  <p>  <p>Meanwhile, the manifesto earned the Unabomber an almost cult status in America's growing  technophobic counter-culture. "He has become one of those emblems of 20th-century America," says Gar  Smith, a radical environmentalist, in a forthcoming documentary to be broadcast on Channel 4. The FBI showed copies  of the manifesto to dozens of academics in an effort to identify the Unabomber - but the suspect's own  family appears to have beaten them to it.  <p>  <p>In Lincoln yesterday, most people who knew him were still shaking their heads in disbelief.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
