 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Blunder over faulty HIV test</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Blunder over faulty HIV test</b><br><br><br><b><h2>6 April 1996</h2></b><br><h2>'Blunder' over  faulty HIV test</h2><h3> Callers besiege Aids agencies  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Vivek Chaudhary</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The Government was last night facing fierce criticism over its handling of the HIV testing scare,  as tens of thousands of people anxiously awaited new results to see whether they are clear of the Aids  virus. Aids counselling agencies were besieged by worried callers after reports emerged of a fault in the  test, which is manufactured by the American-based multi-national Abbott Laboratories.  <p>  <p>Up to 40,000 people in Britain could have received a negative result over the past six months.  They, and thousands more across Europe, will have to be re-tested following the disclosure that the  method used was faulty. The Department of Health was criticised for not publicising the fault sooner  and allowing news to seep out via the media during the Easter holiday break, when many clinics and  Aids counselling agencies are closed.  <p>  <p>Harriet Harman, the shadow health secretary, said the fears of those caught up in the scare were  exacerbated by not being able to talk to people in authority over the weekend. She called for a fax to be sent to all hospitals, rather than GPs, giving full information on the  situation so that the public can get details easily, and for a designated hospital in each area for  people to be re-tested if necessary.  <p>  <p>Simon Hughes, Liberal Democrat health spokesman, said: "It would be wrong to panic but it is right  to be concerned."  <p>  <p>Susie Parsons, executive director of London Lighthouse, Europe's largest centre for people  suffering from the HIV virus, said her organisation had been informed that up to 200 people who  originally tested negative could be positive. Ms Parsons added: "We have had hundreds of calls from people who are obviously very worried. We are  the largest HIV centre in Europe but we first heard about the fault through the media. The Department  of Health has not given us any guidance or warnings. We can't believe the lack of information that  Aids counselling agencies have received. We are advising people to ring the centre that did their  test."  <p>  <p>Dr Graham Winyard, the Deputy Chief Medical Officer, expressed his "deep regret" for the way the  information had got out through the press. But he insisted the chances of a wrong diagnosis were  "very, very tiny". "We were planning to make the situation public next week when more detailed  arrangements could have been made," he told BBC Radio. "It's unfortunate that this has come out now  and led to a lot of unnecessary distress. "This is a very rare fault in the test. The majority of  people who had negative tests will remain negative."  <p>  <p>Laboratories across Britain and Europe were warned of the fault by the Chicago-based Abbott  Laboratories on 29 March. Spokesman Mat Kuhn said the company stopped distributing the tests on 25  March. He added: "We took the action following reports of a small number of inaccurate results. We  informed all our customers and relevant health authorities across Europe and we are working with them  to resolve the situation."  <p>  <p>Blood samples from those tested negative since 25 September 1995, when this particular form of the  Abbott test was introduced, are being re-tested and it could take up to a month before new results are  released. So far three incorrect test results have been identified in Britain, four in Germany and two  in France.  <p>  <p>The Dutch health ministry said about 50,000 people would have to be re-tested. The German health  ministry said 650,000 of the two million affected tests had already been sold. Italian, Swedish and  Danish medical authorities have also ordered re-testing.  <p>  <p>The fault is thought to have been discovered by a Portsmouth doctor who noticed a negative result  for somebody who clearly had Aids.   <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
