 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - James Goldsmith threatens the Tories</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>James Goldsmith threatens the Tories</b><br><br><br><b><h2>29 April 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Tories in a tizz</h2>
<h3>Is Sir James really such a demon?  </h3>  <br><b>Leading article</b><br><br><br>      <p>None of the issues which the Eurosceptics pursue from time to time is unimportant or even only of  narrow party concern. As the Labour MEP Shaun Spiers argues in a challenging article on our Arena page  this morning, all of them would confront a future Labour government every bit as much as they confront  the Conservatives today. All of them are also powerful questions with some electoral potential. The  problem with the Tory Eurosceptics, however, is that they have absolutely no perspective about their  obsession. Thinking about little except the European Union, and misinterpreting widespread popular  irritation against aspects of the European project for fundamentalist opposition to the whole of it,  the Eurosceptics imagine that they are more popular than they really are, and are therefore  increasingly led into overplaying their hand.  <p>  <p>Nowhere is this currently on display more vividly than in the Eurosceptics' live-now-pay-later love  affair with Sir James Goldsmith's Referendum Party. Sir James presents himself as a great national  figure. The Eurosceptics love his message and relay it back to Sir James. The net result is that each  is encouraging the other to believe things which a little calm reflection would show to be nonsense. A  particularly good example of this is the list in Lord Archer's pocket which purports to show the  electoral damage to Tory fortunes which Sir James would cause if he made good his threat to stand in  every seat at the general election, and then took a couple of thousand votes in each one. At the sight  of this list, strong Conservatives are now said to blanch and quail.  <p>  <p>It doesn't take a genius to work out that if everything else stayed the same and Sir James got  those sorts of results, then the Tories would lose 30 seats and Labour would win the election. But  there are so many ifs and buts in this simplistic projection that the calculation is almost entirely  worthless. In particular, there is no evidence that large numbers of people intend to vote for Sir  James anywhere. European election protest votes and the occasional good score in a byelection, as the  Independence Party managed in Staffordshire South East, are extremely unreliable guides to general  election intentions.   <p>  <p>Last week's Times/Mori poll found that only six people in a national sample of  1,947 voters would support the Referendum Party, too small a figure to register as a meaningful  percentage. Future polls may temporarily boost Sir James's score, especially in view of all the  publicity he receives from his media admirers, but come a general election it is extremely improbable  that he will hold on to very much even of that support. No one should blind themselves to the current  churning of mood in this country - and others - about the European Union.   <p>  <p>No one should delude themselves that the European issue is bogus or unimportant. But the atmosphere in the Tory Party  speaks volumes about shattered and desperate Tory nerves and very little about the wider and more  generally alienated political mood. Far be it from us to intrude on private grief, but a serious  political party surely ought to count to 10 before it relies upon the combined judgment of two such  men as Sir James Goldsmith and Lord Archer.   <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
