 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Diana, 'Queen of hearts', slated for being photographed watching  a heart operation </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Diana slated for being photographed watching a heart operation  </b><br><br><br><b><h2>23 April 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Princess's surgery 'stunt' slated</h2><h3> The  self-styled 'Queen of Hearts' watched a top surgeon at work  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Gary Younge</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Her aim, she said, was to be the queen of all our hearts. But yesterday the Princess of Wales was  being seen as an ace at self-publicity after she took her role a little too literally. Trailed by television cameras, she watched as Professor Sir Magdi Yacoub performed a four-hour  heart operation on Arnaud Wambo, aged seven, at Harefield hospital, Middlesex.  <p>  <p>Abandoning her more familiar sportswear for a matching sky-blue surgical mask and gown, Diana  claimed witnessing hospital operations was a profound experience. "It is literally seeing life on a  knife edge. It motivates me - it brings meaning to my life," she said.  <p>  <p>But Claire Rayner, an agony aunt and former theatre nurse, attacked the visit as a "stunt" and a  "photo-opportunity". She said: "I am appalled. This is nothing to do with her as an individual,  honestly, except that I think doing charity is about being private and quiet and not being in the  limelight. There is every reason to have other observers... but to have someone going along to gawp  for the sake of gawping. To actually go there to dress up and pretend that she is part of the scene -  because that's all it is - I can't think what the sister in charge is doing. I would not have allowed  it."  <p>  <p>It was the sixth time the princess has watched open heart surgery. Last week she reportedly watched  a mastectomy.  <p>  <p>"I'm a great lover of children and the fact that a little person can have a second opportunity from  my country - I'm very proud to be involved," said the princess. "When I speak about the various  subjects, whatever it is, I find it's more beneficial if I've seen it for myself." She said she hoped her support for the charity, which was set up in Paris, would attract sponsors  to finance more operations.  <p>  <p>A spokesman for the British Medical Association said there was nothing untoward in people who are  not medically trained and have no family connection with the patient attending surgery.  <p>  <p>But a spokeswoman for the Royal College of Nursing, who saw the princess on television, said:  "Normally everybody in theatre should have their hair tucked away. They shouldn't have make-up and  they wouldn't normally be wearing watches and jewellery."  <p>  <p>Wambo was brought from Cameroon by the charity, Chain of Hope, for surgery not available in his  country, to mend a hole in his heart. Sir Magdi said he was suffering from the congenital heart condition, Fallot Syndrome. He was  precisely the kind of child the charity hoped to help "because we want to have maximum impact on the  lifestyle as well as the longevity of the child".  <p>  <p>Cardiologist Dr Rosemary Radley-Smith predicted that Wambo, who hopes to be able to play football  after his operation, would be "running around" within four or five days and should now lead a normal  life.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p><b>Mercy missions</b>  <p>  <p>The Princess of Wales, interviewed on 'Panorama', 20 November: "I'd like to be a queen of  people's hearts, in people's hearts."  <p>  <p>24 November: Visits Argentina's infantile paralysis association. <p>  <p>3 December: Makes secret night  visits to sick and dying in London hospitals, according to the News of the World.  <p>  <p>4 December: Daily Mirror claims Diana has visited a mother and daughter who are dying of Aids.  <p>  <p>22 February: Hugs a blind boy with a brain tumour at Shaukat Khanum hospital in Pakistan,  founded by the former cricketer, Imran Khan.   <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
