 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - National Grid share sale</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>National Grid share sale</b><br><br><br><b><h2>1 May 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Grid takes lion's share of business  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Paul Murphy</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The nervousness which has characterised trading over the past week or so was still noticeable yesterday.  While speculators continued to unwind positions in potential bid stocks (Labroke was the main victim yesterday), the downside was limited by the flurry of activity around National Grid. But the final score on the FT-SE 100, up 8.7 at 3817.9 at the end of the day, disguised the fact that there were a couple of worrying drops during the day - the most serious coming mid-afternoon as the Dow Jones index on Wall Street opened 30 points lower. Reported trading volume of more than one billion shares suggested a boom in business, but almost a quarter of this was accounted for by the one big trade in the Grid.  <p>  <p>The move by brokers James Capel to buy Hanson's 12.5 per cent stake in the Grid at 192.5p a share was discussed all day. Usually, when a broker or investment bank buys such a big stake in any company, it immediately places the stock - either with another single buyer (such as a predator) or, more commonly, with a string of institutions. These are known as 'bought deals,' with the broker simply taking a turn.  <p>  <p>It quickly became clear yesterday morning that Capel's move on the Grid was different. The only trade printed on the stock market's trade reporting system was the business with Hanson. The expected follow up of a string of trades with institutions failed to materialise - triggering speculation that something had gone badly wrong at Capel, that it might have failed to place the stock and been left, instead, with a &#163;400m liability on its trading book.  <p>  <p>It was only just before market business came to an official close that the broker disclosed a few details of the derivatives transaction it has struck with the Saudis. Shares in National Grid subsequently closed 6p higher at 205p and Hanson added 0.5p to 197.5p, while shares in Capel's highly rated parent, HSBC, crept 2p higher to 984p.  <p>  <p>Elsewhere, it was the turn of Ladbroke to face the profit takers and the stock fell 7.5p to 195.5p as a result. Last week, the City was braying for a bid for the hotels-to-gaming group, with Scottish & Newcastle widely predicted to be the most likely predator. Scottish & Newcastle itself lost 3p to 688p yesterday. Amongst other recent takeover favourite's, the pressure was still on Standard Chartered, off 4p at 622p, while a few nervous types were selling out of Cable & Wireless, down 3.5p at 521.5p as the talks with British Telecom continue.  <p>  <p>National Power, facing attention from across the Atlantic, also succumbed to a bit of selling, closing 10p lower at 561p.  <p>  <p>On a more positive note, there was a sudden rally in Argos just before the close, leaving the market price a net 21p higher at 649p in brisk trading. Dealers insisted the move was a very technical one, simply reflecting a shortage of stock amongst market makers.  <p>  <p>Glaxo Wellcome also ended the day on a strong note, up 14p at 806p after an advisory board to the US Food and Drug Administration recommended that the drug regulator clear Glaxo's new general anesthetic, Ultiva. Amongst the bio-technology stocks, British Biotech continued its run, with a few brave punters paying &#163;30 apiece for the shares at one stage in the afternoon. Late in the day, however, there was a sudden rush to take profits, cutting the day's gain to 50p, with the stock at &#163;29.25. Cortecs International was also hit, closing 19p lower at 394p. TI Group closed up 10p to 547p as the company made a presentation to analysts, while BAT Industries ended the session 11p higher at 502.5p ahead of today's first quarter figures. Most of this rise came during the last half-hour of business, suggesting the figures may have leaked. AromaScan, the 'electronic nose' company, added 5p to 181p after news that it has signed a five-year development and marketing deal with Japan's Mitsubishi Electric covering the British firm's sensor technology. It remained unclear whether the market had woken up to how significant the deal is for AromaScan, which just a month or so ago was warning on profits and trying to explain how long it takes to finalise alliances such as the one with Mitsubishi.  <p>  <p>Close followers say the Japanese group took 15 months to carefully evaluate AromaScan's technology and check out the competition. Alliances with other players in other parts of the world are expected, and broker Credit Lyonnais Laing now reckons the company will be profitable by the end of next year. Cray Electronics jumped 5p to 48p after a trading up-dated, released ahead of year-end figures due in early July. The firm reported "steady progress", but followers who have watched this former stock market rocket come back to earth like the proverbial stick seemed more interested in a statement that the company's cash position has now "stabilised" after the huge losses reported for the past 18 months.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
