 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Arthur Scargill launches the Socialist Labour Party on  May Day </TITLE></HEAD> <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea"  vlink="#adeaea"> <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right  BORDER="0"></A> <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br>
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Arthur Scargill  launches the Socialist Labour Party on May Day </b><br><br><br><b><h2>4 May  1996</h2></b><br><h2>Arthur and ego guard the flame</h2><h3>Arthur Scargill is back, with his  own party and all his old bounce, fired by an unshakeable faith</h2> <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Joanna  Coles</b><br><br>      <p> <p>Arthur Scargill arrives late and lopsided, weighed down by an enormous bulging leather  bag, his hair a fretful fuzz. "I'm knackered," he says, attacking the tea and coffee-making  facilities left out by the NUM lawyers in whose offices we are meeting. "I'll stir," I offer,  waving a spoon towards the teapot he has just filled. He grins: "Typical journalist, always  stirring things." <p> <p>In fact, he looks anything but knackered, he is glowing. Energy throbs  through his face, his hair bristles with static. After something of a fallow period, Arthur has  bounced back into the news and clearly, Arthur is happiest when he is in the public eye.  Wednesday's launch of his new Socialist Labour Party went well, "there were 100 reporters and  six camera crews in attendance!" There was a one-to-one with Jeremy Paxman on Newsnight which  was good because Arthur likes an audience. To be more precise, he likes performing. God knows  what happens to him when he's alone; maybe he simply disappears. But for now he is here, and I  am curious to know where this abundance of energy comes from. <p> <p>"You're only the second  person that has ever asked me that," he says, pleased. "The other person was Billy Graham, the  evangelist. It's interesting. We met for two hours in 1985 and Billy said (at this point  Scargill breaks into a plausible imitation of the American) 'You know Arrthurrr, one of the  things people say to me is: How on earth does Arthur Scargill keep going, against all the  ahdds? You seem to have this tremmennus ability to bounce back. What keeps you going?'I just  looked at him, and I said, it's called faith, Billy. He looked at me and he said, 'I  unnerstand.'" <p> <p>Billy, of course, was talking about his Christian faith whilst Arthur was  talking about socialism. But faith is the right word here; Arthur burns with righteous Old  Testament indignation. His energy comes from his anger, what spurs him on is his capacity for  feeling outrage. <p> <p>His invective towards New Labour is on an Olympian scale. "If the  church to which you went decided to stop worshipping God and started worshipping the devil, you  would have second thoughts," he declaims, when I suggest that starting a new party might be an  overreaction to Labour's dumping of Clause Four. <p> <p>"The leadership of New Labour has  abandoned their socialist faith and embraced capitalism which is tantamount to embracing the  devil!" We will come back to Arthur's firebrand socialism, but first I would like to know a few  personal details. For starters, is it true that he forbade his only daughter Margaret, a GP  aged 31, to marry her fiance Justin Maitland because he wasn't good enough? <p> <p>"I never  speak about my family." Yes, but the wedding was called off at the last minute in March, and  Justin told the Daily Mail that "people don't realise what a terrible snob he [Arthur] is". Did  Arthur, as was alleged at the time, force Margaret to choose between them because he'd had a  row with Justin's father, an Australian trade unionist? "I never speak about my family. I think  it is proper that I should not do so." <p> <p>This, though disappointing, is fair enough.  Scargill is not one of those public figures who peddles the image of a happy family for his own  personal/political gain. <p> <p>But how important are his family to him? Do they give him  strength to continue his fight against capitalist forces? "I've been involved in politics since  I was 14, I wasn't married then and I didn't have children," he says pointedly. <p> <p>Later on  he throws in that he "was offered a place at Oxford but I didn't go because I was married with  a wife and child." This, I think, is meant to sound like a generous sacrifice made on their  behalf; instead, it comes out as slightly peevish, as if he now regrets the decision. <p>  <p>But then Arthur's life turns out to be full of opportunities that he has resolutely refused  to countenance. "I could have been an MP at least six times," he tells me twice. "I'm talking  about rock solid Labour seats offered to me, when I was an extremely 'popular' figure." <p>  <p>He could have gone to grammar school too, he was bright enough, but even aged 10 he was  sufficiently stubborn to refuse to sit the 11 plus. The grammar school was in Barnsley and he  didn't want to leave his home in Worsbrough. A decision he also regrets. <p> <p>He lives there  still, on the outskirts of this grim mining village, in a stone house called Treelands with a  small goldfish pond at the front. But it's hard to imagine him kicking off his Hush Puppies and  curling up on a sofa. He is quick to tell me that in the last week alone, he has travelled more  than 1,000 miles between speaking engagements. <p> <p>"In Salford I spoke to 1,200 economics  students; in Leeds Town Hall, 1,100; in Manchester 1,500; in Swansea there were 450 people  present and in Cardiff they turned 200 people away! In Manchester, they were queueing down the  stairs..." Yes, yes, but what does he do at home? "I watch television actually. I like 'Morse' and  'The Two Ronnies' were extremely good. I like TV because I can read the paper at the same time.  When I went to university in Leeds, one of my tutors, who was an aide to Winston Churchill,  taught me to read newspapers very quickly. You glance down the page like a scanner. It is a  unique facility!" <p> <p>As I left the office to meet him, several female colleagues confided  they find Scargill "oddly sexy". It is obvious he enjoys being the centre of attention, does he  think of himself as attractive? <p> <p>"Are you serious?" He shines for a moment. "I have never  considered that question in my life! I will say though that I find I can work with women much,  much easier than with men. Working with women does not have the same conflicts, or the same  competitiveness as with men." <p> <p>(Afterwards, I wish I'd asked him how he coped for 20  years down the mine with only men for company. But interviewing Scargill is like asking  strangers for directions. You can get distracted by their mannerisms.) He continues, smiling.  "For example, the way this interview has been conducted has more understanding, on both sides,  than if you had been a man. I remember being interviewed by a man who became aggressive, well  you know, I am a coal miner from Yorkshire and I begin to react! The moment anyone cross  examines me in an aggressive way I respond. <p> <p>"One of the most classic interviews ever  done in the history of television was between Peter Snow and me. I am also told that it is now  used as an interview to show journalists what not to do! I really forced him into backing down  and taking back something he said, because what he was putting to me was untrue." And just for  a second his pale eyes dart off into the middle distance, as if he is briefly reliving this  triumph. <p> <p>The aggression thing is understandable; symbols of it abound throughout his  life. From the image of the mine itself, to his one-time hobby of judo (he was a green belt but  gave up after breaking his big toe) to his two giant schnauzer dogs which weigh 18 stone  between them. When he's in Yorkshire, he goes to bed around 2am but is up by 6.30am to walk  them four miles a day. But why schnauzers - more commonly associated with the German police?  "We used to breed Airedale terriers," he explains. "But when my daughter moved house she took  the three Airedales with her. She had always argued they were hers and I accepted that," he  adds, hinting at another unresolved family tension. "Emotionally we didn't want to get another  Airedale, so we decided to get a schnauzer." <p> <p>Are they an extension of himself? "Oh they  are not aggressive like rottweilers. They're magnificent with children. The bitch is a bit  naughty with other dogs, but the dog is fine." <p> <p>And Arthur is fine too, far less prickly  than I'd expected from his television appearances. In fact, he is wildly charming, performing  funny little cameos of his old tutors (which involve lots of Arthur mimicking a posh voice) and  listening with the unfailing attention of a dictaphone. His sincerity about socialism is never  in doubt. But then neither is his enormous ego. "I am not an egomaniac," he says emphatically.  "If I was I would have gone for the gravy train special, I would have gone to parliament." <p>  <p>But isn't that just where he's hoping to go? "I have never had any desire to be an MP." So  why form a political party? "I want to ensure we have a political party that puts into words  its principle of faith, but has a practical means of putting them into action." <p> <p>But  surely that means being an MP? "I would not rule it out for the reason that the party may feel  there are circumstances where I should stand." But Arthur is the new party, and in our  conversation all roads lead back to Arthur. Take the following simple and ostensibly Arthurless  question. Does he think Tony Blair is charismatic? "The only memory I have of Tony is when he  first spoke with me, when he spoke as a young newly elected MP, when he said it was one of the  proudest moments in his life to speak alongside one of the greatest trade union leaders in  Britain, Arthur Scargill." It is as if he is stuck in his own Scargillian groove. He even  speaks with his own Scargillian syntax, which has a formal, almost biblical flavour. Words are  rarely abbreviated - I had is rarely shortened to I'd; it's remains it is. <p> <p>And Arthur  Scargill remains the same too. "There has been no change in the way I have reacted all through  my life," he says proudly. "It is no different now than it has always been." <p> <p> <p> <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td  width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td  width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td  width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG  SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td width=40><A  HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td> <td  width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td> </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr> <td  align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A  HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td> <td align=right  valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td> </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
