 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Helen Dunmore wins first Orange prize for women writers worth 30,000 </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Helen Dunmore wins first Orange prize for women writers worth 30,000 </b><br><br><br><b><h2>16 May 1996</h2></b><br><h2>British writer wins women's book prize  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Dan Glaister</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The National Liberal Club in London reverberated to whoops and cheers last night when the British writer Helen Dunmore was awarded the first Orange prize for women writers of fiction for her novel 'A Spell of Winter'. Ms Dunmore was presented with a statuette, called a Bessie, and a cheque for &#163;30,000 by the actress Juliet Stevenson. The prize for women fiction writers in the English language came down to a choice between Ms Dunmore's novel, the bookmakers' favourite, and 'Eveless Eden', by the American-born writer resident in Britain, Marianne Wiggins.  <p>  <p>Other authors shortlisted were Briton Julia Blackburn, with 'The Book of Colour', and Americans Pagan Kennedy with 'Spinsters', Amy Tan with 'The Hundred Secret Senses', and Anne Tyler with 'Ladder of Years'.  <p>  <p>Speaking before presenting the prize, Ms Stevenson confessed that she "was normally rather ambivalent about prizes and awards." The Orange prize, however, was an exception. "I am not in favour generally of separatism," said the actress, "but I have only worked twice in pieces written by women in 18 years in the theatre."  <p>  <p>Kate Mosse, chair of the judges, brushed aside criticism of the women-only prize, saying that it served to sell books.  <p>  <p>The Orange prize has been dogged by controversy. Born out of the Booker prize, the Orange followed in the best traditions of Britain's most famous literary award when the judges fell out as soon as the shortlist was announced. Val Hennessy, a member of the five-woman panel and chief book reviewer for the Daily Mail, said that of the 146 that had been submitted for the prize, she had "seldom come across books that were so bad". The prize was sparked by the late writer Angela Carter's failure to make the 1991 Booker Prize shortlist for her final novel, 'Wise Children'. Only four out of 30 nominees for the Booker in the last five years have been women, while women have won the Nobel prize for literature on only eight occasions this century.  <p>  <p>Intended to counter perceived discrimination, the Orange prize succeeded in attracting charges of discrimination and political correctness. Organisers argued that the Orange, open to women of any nationality writing in English, was more open than any of the other prizes, pointing out that the Booker is restricted to Commonwealth writers.  <p>  <p>Alarmed by the bad publicity, the initial sponsors of the prize, Mitsubishi, withdrew support in September 1994. It seemed that the project would falter, until an anonymous woman benefactor provided the &#163;30,000 prize money in perpetuity, and Orange, the mobile telephone company, decided to sponsor the award with a commitment to spend &#163;210,000 over the next three years.  <p>  <p>The Orange's &#163;30,000 is the second most lucrative prize on the literary awards circuit. The most prize money goes to the winner of the National Literature Prize, while the NCR Book Award offers &#163;25,000, the Whitbread &#163;21,500, and the Booker &#163;20,000.  <p>  <p>Ironically, the most recent winners of both the Booker and the Whitbread have been women: Pat Barker for 'The Ghost Road', and Kate Atkinson for 'Behind the Scenes At the Museum'.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
