 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Roy Hattersley, Lord Hanson, and now Joy Johnson is taking aim at the media. Stop blaming the messenger (877) </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Lord Hanson criticises cynical media for weakening nation </b><br><br><br><b><h2>17 May 1996 </h2></b><br><h2>Roy Hattersley, Lord Hanson, and now Joy Johnson is taking aim at the media - Stop blaming the messenger </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Roy Greenslade</b><br><br>      <p>Is journalism in crisis? The question is as old as newspapers, but that doesn't stop people asking it. Consider a handful of the most recent critics. Businessman Lord Hanson warns of "destructive journalism" which shows a lurid interest in the private lives of public figures and is thereby destroying public trust.  <p>  <p>Former Labour party spin-doctor Joy Johnson, in a speech delivered at a conference on Saturday, repents the error of her ways, arguing that the relationship between politicians and lobby journalists have turned into a game which threatens the democratic process. Politician Roy Hattersley laments soundbite journalism, accusing serious television interviewers of indulging in showbiz rather than sensible debate.  <p>  <p>And because navel-gazing is a media obsession, a couple of journalists have joined in too. Independent editor Andrew Marr promotes a law to protect privacy as a way of diverting political debate away from the bedroom. One of Marr's most distinguished contributors, Bryan Appleyard, worries that a corruption of news values means that democracy is in danger of being undermined. All of these arguments echo, both consciously and unconsciously, those of James Fallows, the American journalist whose book 'Breaking The News: How The Media Undermine American Democracy' was featured on these pages some weeks ago.  <p>  <p>The danger, however, is to give all of these critics the same weight and respect. For example, Hanson argued in the Spectator that adversarial interviewing techniques foster "the belief that politicians routinely evade the truth and break their promises." In his view, our politicians are not corrupt. Similarly businessmen are, says Hanson, "castigated for seeking profit". Hanson claims that this cynical approach "creates a climate in which trust in society as a whole dissolves". The nation is therefore weakened.  <p>  <p>When pressed on Radio 4's Today programme - which he appeared, surprisingly, to exclude from his criticisms - Hanson's ringing indictment of journalism was quickly reduced to a tinkle. Surely, said John Humphrys, the public was able to see through the superficial form of an interview to its content. People were too intelligent to be taken in. Hanson agreed. That did not destroy his argument, as Humphrys triumphantly suggested, but merely showed that Hanson had not thought it through.  <p>  <p>No one who believes in the media's power to shape its audience's perspective would maintain that the process is one of cause and effect. Humphrys also failed to point out the self-serving nature of Hanson's attack: fat cat businessmen have become a target even for rightwing newspapers, with the Daily Mail last week running a trenchant leader and a wickedly funny cartoon.  <p>  <p>Joy Johnson, keen to distance her arguments from those of Hanson, thought him guilty of calling for "a timid feel-good press" while she was doing the opposite: demanding a bolder journalism, free from Westminster's cosy relationships between the lobby, the party press advisers and MPs. Her views strike a chord. Journalists don't like spin-doctors; politicians don't like spin-doctors; the public are being encouraged not to like spin-doctors. Now we have a spin-doctor who doesn't like spin-doctors.  <p>  <p>But she overstates her case. To claim that the fall in the esteem of politicians is directly related to the rise in "the arts of the spin-doctors" is plainly wrong in almost every respect. The public's lack of respect for MPs has been growing throughout the post-war period and its acceleration in recent years is only partially due to the press. Many factors have played a part, such as the way in which ex-Cabinet ministers end up with strings of lucrative directorships and sitting MPs make so much money on the side. (Hanson, please note, calls parliament "one of the most incorrupt in the world"). The sexual sleaze revealed in tabloids is probably far less influential.  <p>  <p>Marr also lends too much weight to such intrusion. Unsavoury though some of it is, there is little evidence that it affects voters. It is the establishment which turns it into an issue by blackballing its victims and forcing needless resignations. Those who face it out, such as Paddy Ashdown and Steven Norris, have not suffered. Rather than introducing a privacy law, the best way to divert newspapers is to ignore it. Lack of controversy defeats the sales-building objective.  <p>  <p>This is not to say that Hanson and Johnson, along with Appleyard, have not raised serious issues. The problem with the debate thus far is that too much is made of too little. (How can a soundbite world really affect democracy, Mr Hattersley?) There is no coherent, comprehensive analysis of where journalism is heading. Too many of the critics are too subjective, giving us opinions in the place of evidence. How many times have we been told that investigative journalism is over? How often must we hear that politics has been trivialised because it deals with personalities rather than policies? It sounds fine, but after a moment's thought we realise there has never been a political system - totalitarian or liberal democratic - where politics has been divorced from human beings. Journalism is ill-served by those who think the messenger is always the problem.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
