 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - WPC Karen Wade loses sexual harassment claim at industrial tribunal </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>WPC Karen Wade loses sexual harassment claim at industrial tribunal </b><br><br><br><b><h2>21 May 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Harassment case WPC "has no regrets"</h2><h3>Many policewomen are developing defence mechanisms to cope with sexist colleagues  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Duncan Campbell</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The case of Karen Wade, the policewoman who lost her sexual harassment claim at an industrial tribunal in Leeds yesterday, will not be the last in which allegations of sexism are raised by officers against their colleagues. She did not regret bringing the case, she said outside the court. "I believe I have given strength to others who find themselves in similar situations to my own, to stand up and challenge the treatment they are receiving." In the past two years the Police Federation has been involved in 250 cases of alleged sexual or racial harassment, and the number is increasing annually.  <p>  <p>Yesterday, the federation, which represents officers up to the rank of inspector, confirmed there had been a significant increase in such actions, which it felt reflected similar civil actions taken elsewhere in society. Fred Broughton, chairman of the federation, said yesterday: "No other staff association or union has spent more on such cases."  <p>  <p>He took exception to suggestions, following the federation's decision not to finance Ms Wade's action, that it did not fight on behalf of women. The federation always acted on legal advice as to whether cases should be pursued. Sometimes it acted for both the officer making the complaint and those against whom it had been made.  <p>  <p>Last night Tony Burden, chief constable of Gwent and spokesman on equal opportunities for the Association of Chief Police Officers, said: "Allegations of sexual discrimination are taken extremely seriously by chief police officers." Individuals might decide they would prefer the matter to be dealt with by an industrial tribunal.  <p>  <p>Women make up 16 per cent of constables and 14 per cent of the service as a whole. The percentage is increasing every year.  <p>  <p>Policewomen who voice complaints about male behaviour are known as "walking ITs" among some male officers. This means they believe the women will eventually go to an industrial tribunal (IT) with an allegation about sexist behaviour. For this the male officers blame the 'equal opportunities industry' and 'politically correct' senior officers.  <p>  <p>Even women who win their cases face problems. Sarah Locker, who won a &#163;32,500 compensation claim from the Metropolitan police and an unprecedented public apology in 1993, said she was shunned when she returned to work, and anonymous calls blamed her for the fact that after her case many male detectives were transferred back into uniform. "No woman officer embarks lightly on an action," Mrs Locker said yesterday. "There's a lot of thought goes into it and a lot of sacrifices made."  <p>  <p>For every Sarah Locker, there are many others who say nothing. Women officers complain that if they play along with male banter too much they are accused of being 'slags' and if they make clear their displeasure, they are called 'lessies'.  <p>  <p>"If you respond to a remark, you are on your hobby horse; if you don't, they take it as agreement," said one woman constable quoted in the report on equal opportunities completed by the Inspectorate of Constabulary last year. The report found a high level of "sexist banter, perhaps more covert and subtle than before but no less destructive". It also concluded that "many women... felt that anyone who raised issues would be denigrated, ignored or dealt with inappropriately, and most had developed coping mechanisms to continue with work which they valued highly."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
