 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - WPC Karen Wade loses sexual harassment claim at industrial tribunal </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>WPC Karen Wade loses sexual harassment claim at industrial tribunal </b><br><br><br><b><h2>21 May 1996</h2></b><br><h2>The accused</h2><H3>A spate of recent cases featuring high-profile men has refocused attention on the question of sexual harassment </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Mark Lawson</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The new biographies of Howard Hughes and Joe Kennedy established once again that prominent, powerful men of the past had a great deal of sex. Events of the past few weeks, however, have suggested that what today's famous males are most likely to get are sexual harassment suits. British tycoon Richard Branson has been accused by a former American employee of improperly fondling her at a party. Nobel prize-winning West Indian poet Derek Walcott faces allegations from a former student at Boston University of marking down her work because she refused to have sex with him. A former personal assistant to the actor George C Scott is suing him for allegedly making sexual advances to her, including the request that she have his baby. In Australia, motorbike star Barry Sheene and racing driver Gerhard Berger have been accused of unwanted intimacy with a teenage shop assistant. Meanwhile, in Washington DC, President Clinton's lawyers continue trying to delay a sexual harassment suit from a woman who claims that, in a hotel room in Arkansas in 1991, he dropped his trousers and ordered her to perform oral sex.  <p>  <p>All the men firmly deny and are contesting the claims. But this spate of cases featuring high-profile men has refocused attention on the question of sexual harassment. Some believe that, as with domestic violence and racial discrimination before it, a long ignored social problem is finally being remedied by the legal system. Others contend that the law has opened up a rich new source of income for American lawyers and litigants and offered a glittering instrument of revenge to women with a grudge against men. It is significant that the cases outlined above are all being pursued outside the British legal system, four in America and one in Australia. America has long had both federal and state laws forbidding sexual harassment (broadly defined as unwanted attention, physical or verbal, of a sexual nature) at work. Most major US companies now bind their male employees to codes of conduct, which forbid, for example, uninvited comment on a female colleague's appearance or a second social request after a first has been declined. The country's system of civil personal injury suits - of the kind being brought by relatives of the victims in the OJ Simpson case - also allows for massive financial claims to be brought against prominent individuals or institutions. The woman in the Walcott case, for example, is seeking several million dollars.  <p>  <p>"We're going to see more and more of these cases in America," says Richard North Patterson, a San Francisco-based attorney and author of legal thrillers. "How the American legal system works is that it identifies a problem - and sexual harassment of women has been a genuine problem - then defines a right enforceable by law. And once lawyers work out how to bring and win a case, you get a flood of them." British law is far less advanced. Sexual harassment cases are covered by the Sex Discrimination Act of 1975, which deals with all prejudice against employees on grounds of gender. Such cases are heard by an industrial tribunal. (Yesterday, Karen Wade, a police sergeant who complained of a "culture of sexual harassment" up to and including "indecent assault" in the West Yorkshire police force, lost her case.) British workers are also covered by two pieces of European legislation: a 1991 Code of Recommendations on Dignity in The Workplace and a 1976 Equal Treatment Directive.  <p>  <p>There are three basic theories of sexual harassment suits: whistleblowing, gold-digging and revenge. The first insists that office monsters are being caged; the second that a new female-only National Lottery has been invented; the third that the law hath no fury like a woman scorned. Masculine popular culture has generally favoured the second and third theories. David Mamet's play and film Oleanna showed a weak student deliberately destroying her professor's career with a false claim of sexual harassment. Michael Crichton's book and film Disclosure suggested the real crisis in the workplace is female harassment of men.  <p>  <p>The reason sexual harassment is such a contentious area of litigation is that the evidence is often merely a matter of opinion. Apart from those relating to marriage and divorce, there are four areas of the law concerning sexual behaviour. These are rape, stalking, 'date rape' and sexual harassment. Although the first two are by no means straightforward prosecutions - parliamentary attempts to introduce a specific law against stalking were recently frustrated - there will generally be some forensic or police evidence.  <p>  <p>The difficulty in both 'date rape' (when assault is alleged to have occurred during an originally consensual encounter) and sexual harassment is that the evidence tends to come down to two conflicting verbal accounts of what took place. This has the effect of permitting - or, some believe, encouraging - vexatious litigation, revenge allegations. Accuse a man of murder and the law will require some proof; allege sexual harassment and your story alone, at least in America, will usually be enough to begin legal proceedings. "Any 'he said, she said' area of law is obviously susceptible to abuse," says Richard North Patterson. However, Mary Stacey - a specialist in equality law at the London solicitors Thompsons - insists that, at least in a British context, the perception that these cases proceed solely by accusation is false.  <p>  <p>"In the case of straightforward sexual harassment - groping against the photocopier, as it were - it will usually be her word against his and it's a question of who is more believable," she says. "But in cases of denied promotion or discrimination against a woman who has rejected someone's advances, there will often be witnesses or evidence. We would usually advise someone in such a situation to keep a diary." Whatever the doubts that have arisen in some cases, there is no doubt that the worlds of business and education have, for decades, housed large numbers of male sexual predators, who used their powers of hiring and grading, promotion and preferment, to demand sex. It may also be the case that these conditions applied even more so on the celebrity circuit. Without commenting directly on the George C Scott case, it is well-documented in the literature of Hollywood that there have been many prominent figures who claimed droit du seigneur. Without commenting directly on the Bill Clinton case, the literature of Washington establishes that the political arena has featured senators, governors and even presidents who asked for sex from female employees. There is, for example, a famous story of the White House secretary who woke to find Lyndon Johnson sliding into her bed, with the words: "Move over, honey, it's your President." There were doubtless many women who were happy to say yes in such circumstances - power can be an aphrodisiac for both sides - but equally there will have been those who felt compelled to submit because of the position of their seducer. Some of the law suits of recent years result from their understanding that they no longer have to.  <p>  <p>"The good news," Richard North Patterson says, "is that increased education and evolving consciousness in this area are ultimately going to make the workplace far more amenable for women. The bad news is that there are going to be bogus law suits. That's the price you pay." Here, gold-digging is less likely, because of the small amounts of gold on offer - average payment from industrial tribunals is &#163;12,712 - and the complexity of the procedure. "It's harder to bring a claim than not to bring one," Mary Stacey says. "I've seen no evidence of vendetta claims in the cases I've handled. I do think, though, that workplace relationships are far more complex than ever comes out at tribunal."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
