 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Sir Hugh Annesley announces retirement</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Sir Hugh Annesley announces retirement</b><br><br><br><b><h2>22 May 1996</h2></b><br><h2>RUC chief steps down after seven years</h2><h3>Top man says he felt duty bound to remain in job for two years longer than intended  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Sharrock</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The RUC chief constable, Sir Hugh Annesley, announced yesterday that he is retiring in November after seven years in the job.  <p>  <p>Sir Hugh said he had intended to serve for five years. "In the middle of 1994, however, a ceasefire was imminent and I felt a clear duty, and a personal desire, to remain to steer the force through that difficult period." It was now time for a fresh pair of hands to lead the RUC into the next century.  <p>  <p>Sir Hugh leaves at a crucial moment for the force and Northern Ireland, as the RUC readies itself for the most sweeping changes since the onset of the troubles necessitated a shift towards military-style policing. A fundamental internal review is near publication, but implementation of its proposals is unlikely in the event of renewed paramilitary violence. Sir Hugh said: "The RUC is, in my view, a quite outstanding police service. Courageous, adaptable and committed, it has made a huge contribution to the stability of this province and to the well-being of all who reside here. Despite the challenges and difficulties throughout my time, it has been an absolute privilege and honour to lead this fine organisation." His replacement - who will be appointed by the Police Authority for Northern Ireland subject to the Northern Ireland Secretary's approval - is likely to be one of his two deputies, Ulstermen Blair Wallace<SUP>1</SUP> or Ronnie Flanagan<SUP>2</SUP>. The latter enjoys a relatively high public profile, and his future may be determined by how he handles this summer's marching season.  <p>  <p>Sir Hugh was born in 1939 into a wealthy Dublin Protestant family. In 1958 he joined the Metropolitan police, fulfilling a boyhood ambition. He commanded virtually every major branch in the Met and Sussex forces, including specialist operations liaising with the RUC on anti-terrorist work.  <p>  <p>He arrived in Ulster in the tense summer of 1989, scoring an immediate propaganda success by walking the length of the nationalist Falls Road at the head of a republican march. But the police authority had wanted someone else, so did the Northern Ireland Office and Sir Hugh emerged as the unhappy compromise.  <p>  <p>He was unfairly nicknamed 'the eternal flame' because, according to his critics, he never goes out. Last year, the Ulster Unionist security spokesman, Ken Maginnis, pointedly asked in the Commons how many nights Sir Hugh had spent in the province.  <p>  <p>Sir Hugh fought off legal attempts to have the Stalker report into shoot-to-kill allegations published. He will be remembered as a sturdy defender of his force, successfully suing Channel 4 when it broadcast a programme which alleged RUC officers were helping to target and murder IRA suspects.  <p>  <p>His policy was to contain terrorism, not to attempt to eradicate it, believing a political settlement was the only real solution to the province's problems.  <p>  <p>He said yesterday that draconian security measures such as internment did not work. "In my view internment may have been a short-term palliative but it would never have been a long-term solution."  <p>  <p>Sir Hugh said he believed the Shankill and Greysteel massacres in 1993 were a turning point and the terms of the IRA ceasefire - a 'complete' cessation - almost a year later had been more than had been expected at the time. "The ceasefire had become almost inevitable. I had always said that on balance I thought it would hold. It was a unanimous view of the intelligence community. But that was always subject to how the political developments would run and when they ran into some difficulties the balanced scenario shifted."  <p>  <p>He had been surprised by the timing of the breakdown of the ceasefire and was not sure it could be restored in time for the June all-party talks. "If [the IRA] have any sense and if they are looking to the future they will call the ceasefire... because if they do not they will remain on the outside looking in."  <p>  <p>Sir Hugh is thought to be privately critical of the Government's handling of the ceasefire, judging its emphasis on the decommissioning of weapons to have no practical benefit.  <p>  <p>His last annual report this year recorded a near-absence of paramilitary activity, falling crime and the number of Catholics applying to join the RUC - an overwhelmingly Protestant force - up by 20 per cent.  <p>  <p>1.
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Blair Wallace</b>  <p>  <p>Age 58    <br>Joined RUC 1955, serving on border in Armagh and Fermanagh    <br>Promoted to superintendent 1974 and posted to headquarters    <br>Became assistant chief constable 1984    <br>Assumed overall responsibility for tackling crime 1988    <br>Appointed deputy chief constable 1992  <P>  <p>2.
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Ronnie Flanagan</b>    <p>Born and raised in north Belfast 1949    <br>Joined RUC in 1970, serving in all ranks from constable to superintendent in Belfast, Londonderry and in Special Branch    <br>Promoted to chief superintendent and seconded to the Police Staff College at Bramshill 1990    <br>Moved to Command Support, RUC HQ, 1995    <br>Awarded OBE in new year honours list 1996  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=