 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Jaymee Bowen, Child B, dies</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Jaymee Bowen, Child B, loses fight against leukaemia</b><br><br><br><b><h2>29 May 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Farewell to Jaymee, the child who said "don't forget me"  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Nick Varley</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>A steel drum provided a fitting accompaniment. Like the girl at whose funeral it was played, it is more readily thought of as uplifting and lively, but yesterday it rang out a mournful lament to mark the death of Jaymee Bowen, aged 11, and said to be 'an example to all of us'. The last time the family and friends of the girl who will always be remembered as Child B enjoyed such sounds, their happiness was as deep as yesterday's sorrow at Croydon parish church, south London.  <p>  <p>At a special birthday party last year - a celebration her doctors once said she would not see - a rejuvenated Jaymee even showed family friend Aubrey Bryan how she thought he should play his drums.  The gathering in the back garden of the family home came a couple of months after the leukaemia which she had fought for six years was found to be in remission.  <p>  <p>Yesterday, a week after the disease returned to claim Jaymee, Aubrey played again - a piece specially written for her - in front of the 200 mourners. Sarah Barclay, the BBC reporter who spent six months preparing a 'Panorama' programme on the family's fight, told them Jaymee's one wish was to become an ordinary girl. But she added yesterday: "Even if you weren't ill, you couldn't have been just an ordinary girl.  <p>  <p>"Your words of courage made the nation sit up and listen. What words they were: 'I say never give up hope unless you are on the last little drop of life'."  <p>  <p>The most touching wreath was one in the shape of a butterfly. Jaymee said that if there was an afterlife she wanted to come back as a butterfly. The Reverend Colin Boswell told the congregation: "I think the worst thing that can happen to us is to lose a child. However, our lives are properly judged not by their length, but by what they contribute.  <p>  <p>"Her life gave many people courage and hope, hope in the life that perhaps they struggled with as they saw her struggle to find life and to find a way through that which is painful and difficult and hard.  She has been an example to us - not only to other children who are sick, but to all of us - an example of what it is to rise above pain and difficulty."  <p>  <p>That pain and difficulty came to a head in January last year when doctors said that Jaymee had eight weeks to live.  Her father David refused to accept the prognosis and found a private specialist prepared to try further treatment. He failed in a court battle to win NHS funding for it.  Only an anonymous gift of &#163;75,000 allowed Jaymee to undergo further operations and enjoy another year of life.  <p>  <p>As the service drew to a close and mourners filed past the open white coffin, Mr Bowen leaned over and kissed his daughter. Sitting a couple of rows away was his former wife Alyson, who separated from her husband when Jaymee was 2&#189; .  <p>  <p>They had just heard Mike Robinson, producer of the 'Panorama' film, tell one last story of Child B: "Last summer I was driving Jaymee and some of her friends to a swimming pool near where they lived. Jaymee saw my notebook in the car and wrote in it: 'Now that you know me, please don't forget me.' She never said anything when I read it, she just looked. I wish I still had the note. But, Jaymee, I'll never forget you - and I don't think any of us will."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
