 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - American researchers find playing music helps raise maths standards </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>American researchers find playing music helps raise maths standards </b><br><br><br><b><h2>25 May 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Musical pupils score notable maths success  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Donald Macleod</b><br><br>      <p><I>  <p>Brian May, guitarist of the rock group Queen, studied astrophysics at Imperial College, London, which now offers a physics/music performance degree with the Royal College of Music  <p>  <p>Courtney Pine, the leading British jazz saxophonist, according to his agent "can't count when it comes to recording budgets"  <p>  <p>Albert Einstein, was a violinist and played duets with the pianist Artur Rubinstein, who once exclaimed: "The trouble with you Albert is that you can't count"  <p>  <p>Galileo, the son of a musician, might have stayed out of trouble with the Inquisition had he taken up his father's trade</I>  <p>  <p>Playing music improves children's maths results, according to American researchers who put long-held theories of a link to the test. Their findings suggest recent drastic cuts in music tuition in schools are backfiring on ministers and school inspectors as they preach the need to raise standards of basic mathematics.  <p>  <p>Classes of five- to seven-year-olds given special music and arts lessons performed better in maths tests than control groups who were not. Eight out of 10 of the children given tuition in music and arts skills had started behind the control children when they were tested in kindergarten, but overtook them after seven months.  <p>  <p>The same effect was clear the following year, with the highest scores among children with two years' music and arts development, researchers found in Providence, Rhode Island.  <p>  <p>Once the children found playing music and doing visual arts was pleasurable they became motivated to acquire skills, reported Martin Gardiner and his colleagues in the journal 'Nature'.  <p>  <p>The children realised they could learn challenging skills and this improved their general attitude to learning and school. "Learning arts skills forces mental 'stretching' useful to other areas of learning."  <p>  <p>In England and Wales education authority music services have been cut back, but the picture is confused, said Richard Hickman, chief executive of the Federation of Music Services. In some areas the number of children learning instruments has held up or increased, but only because parents are paying more in fees, leading to fears that children from poor families are missing out on the chance to play music.  <p>  <p>Results of national curriculum tests at ages seven and 11 have shown clear links between poverty and the levels reached by children.  <p>  <p>George Odam, music education professor at Bath college of higher education, said the national curriculum had improved schools' awareness of art and music but teacher training in music was being cut to focus on the basics. Boys in cathedral schools performed better in all subjects even when they were not academic because they were learning music. "The left brain and right brain have to interact strongly together with a movement response in music. It is a very unusual activity," said Prof Odam.  <p>  <p>"But those that do give attention to the performance of music are places where something special happens."  <p>  <p>Claims that listening to Mozart improved spatial reasoning skills were tested earlier this year in Britain when 11,000 children in 250 schools were randomly split into three groups. One group listened to a Mozart quintet on Radio 3, one to pop music on Radio 1, and one to conversation on Radio 5 Live.  <p>  <p>In the tests of spatial reasoning the pop listeners scored 56 per cent compared with 52 per cent for the others.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
