 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Elections to all-party talks held in Norther Ireland</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Elections to all-party talks held in Northern Ireland</b><br><br><br><b><h2>25 May 1996</h2></b><br><h2>The Cruiser sets out to prove his new Unionist credentials</h2><h3>Report on Conor Cruise O'Brien's amazing journey  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Sharrock</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Ireland's greatest living man of letters, to use Bob McCartney's phrase, was standing on the spot where Sir Edward Carson, Ulster's greatest hero, signed a Solemn Covenant pledging to oppose Home Rule by all means. Conor Cruise O'Brien didn't look all that impressed with the lavish interior of Belfast City Hall but he did admit: "I've come a long way to get here." The Cruiser, as friends and foes call him, once batted for the Irish Republic. Now he's a member of Mr McCartney's United Kingdom Unionist Party. If he is elected next Thursday in the Northern Ireland elections, the former Irish cabinet minister who faced Unionist leaders across the table at the 1974 Sunningdale negotiations will have completed an extraordinary journey. Facing him on June 10 will be his erstwhile compatriots as, this time around, he argues the Unionist case.  <p>  <p>But he hasn't been cold-shouldered by the Irish establishment for his act of heresy. "Such flak as has been forthcoming has been from people who disliked me before I was a unionist. I didn't expect them to stop!"  <p>  <p>Yesterday morning, as his wife, Maire, drove him up from their home on Howth Hill, north of Dublin, a petrol attendant at a border garage had wished him luck in his Northern Ireland campaign.  <p>  <p>It was a message he brought to Eric Smyth, Belfast's Lord Mayor and a Paisley follower. "I'm here to tell you that there are very few people in the Irish Republic who want to thrust a united Ireland upon you." Mr Smyth looked greatly relieved.  <p>  <p>Dr Cruise O'Brien says that his conversion began during the ill-fated Sunningdale talks. He still believes that what almost emerged from that experiment remains Northern Ireland's best hope for stability and peace. "I argued in cabinet that we shouldn't be emphasising the Council of Ireland and that the important thing was to get the cross-community executive which would be an absolutely historic achievement."  <p>  <p>He believes that his party leader and friend, Bob McCartney QC, the integrationist MP for North Down, is the inheritor of Brian Faulkner's legacy, an anti-sectarian brand of Unionism.  <p>  <p>"After Sunningdale I became the first member of an Irish government to say that I was not working for a united Ireland. That didn't make me a unionist all of a sudden but I did have a good deal of sympathy with them." But in the past three years, with the development of the relationship between the SDLP leader, John Hume, and Sinn Fein president, Gerry Adams, "and the rising influence of Sinn Fein in the politics of the republic I became very alarmed and still am at the direction that things are going." The Irish peace process was aimed at securing a united Ireland "against the known wish of the majority of the population of the province. I side with the unionists in resisting that project. I feel very much at home with the United Kingdom Unionists."  <p>  <p>After tea with the lord mayor he sauntered down Royal Avenue with Mr McCartney and his campaign team. The frail-looking 78-year-old politician, diplomat, newspaper editor and internationally recognised essayist swam into the view of two immaculately coiffed ladies.  <p>  <p>Deep in conversation, they paused as one said to the other: "Jesus Nora, that's Conor Cruise O'Brien!"  <p>  <p>"Ach, I wouldn't give him the light of day Mary, nobody likes a turncoat." "I know, but aren't you sick of hearing from all of them? Nora, I swear, if I see or hear one more politician I will throw up!"  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
