 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Northern Ireland all-party talks begin at Stormont</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Northern Ireland all-party talks begin at Stormont</b><br><br><br><b><h2>10 June 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Time to offer hands of peace</h2><h3>Guilt and blame on every side, as Ulster faces another moment of truth  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Sharrock</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>There is so much history pressing down upon Ireland, it seems almost surprising at times like this that the island manages not to  sink below the Atlantic.  <p>  <p>Today, however, genuinely deserves the epithet 'historic', for at two o'clock this afternoon the British and Irish governments will  open the widest ranging negotiations on Northern Ireland's future ever to be held. The Union with Great Britain (in a formal if not a  practical sense) will be on the table within the talks chamber at Castle Buildings in the grounds of the Stormont estate. The chairman  of the talks will be an internationally respected American advocate and politician, a close friend of President Clinton.  <p>  <p>Barring a one-minute-to-midnight announcement by the IRA that it is restoring its 1994 ceasefire 'unequivocally', we know what will  happen later today. Sinn Fein will turn up at Stormont in order to be turned away, generating the most memorable images of the day. It  will do them little good and they know it. Getting here was not easy. John Major is guilty of mishandling crucial moments since that  ceasefire announcement in September 1994 which brought a tidal wave of change to the ordinary detail of everyday life in Northern  Ireland. Others are guilty of similar misjudgments. Both governments, and the main Unionist and Nationalist parties, are entitled to  be satisfied that they have preserved the essentials of their positions while at the same time having set out a fair route towards a  final agreement.  <p>  <p>There will be a lot of huffing and puffing from the Unionists today about the appointment of the 'Irish American' George Mitchell  as chairman - the Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble yesterday warned of the "bumpy" ride ahead - but it is scarcely credible that  they will get up and walk away from the table now.  <p>  <p>Some senior republicans privately concede that the Irish government has managed to broker the best circumstances for Sinn Fein's  entry into real negotiations, a fact acknowledged by Gerry Adams, Sinn Fein president, at a noisy and colourful rally on Friday to  celebrate its greatest ever electoral success - in Belfast's Ulster Hall, a former bastion of Unionism. Publicity stunts are all very  well - and there isn't a political party in Ireland which doesn't admit that Sinn Fein are unbeatable at them - but certainly not in  today's circumstances.  <p>  <p>In the Irish Republic, 133,000 children will be sitting school examinations that are vitally important to them and their parents.  In Limerick, a Garda detective will be buried with full state honours, attended by a solemn-faced John Bruton before he travels north.  <p>  <p>In spite of the IRA denial, the police are convinced that some of its members shot Gerry McCabe dead in circumstances which one  local officer described as "an execution".  <p>  <p>These are the stories that will dominate the news agenda of the South and on such days the impact of media stunts relating to  Northern Ireland is blunted, particularly after weekend opinion polls showing an overwhelming desire for a restoration of the IRA  ceasefire.  <p>  <p>What then is the alternative for the republican movement? A return to 'armed struggle' and the murder of hundreds more fellow  countrymen and women, bringing the inevitable loyalist retaliation and a new generation of funerals, broken hearts and poisoned minds?  <p>  <p>The IRA can and does talk tough; its people have suffered too and in darker times sustained themselves with the belief that it is  not he who can inflict but endure the most suffering who will emerge the victor.  Nevertheless, the Sinn Fein lexicon underwent stealthy restructuring in the late 1980s and the talk today is of peace and not  victory.  <p>  <p>In the end they would be faced with the finality and reality of the arrangements of today's Stormont talks, but the task of coaxing  the main political participants once more to the table would have been made all the more gruelling.  The republican movement's chief strategists surely know that it would be better to go now and lock everybody into negotiations than  risk losing the chance.  <p>  <p>If today is inauspicious, then so be it. It is a start. The IRA appears to be undergoing an agonising reappraisal of its tactics,  with last Friday's murder of an Irish policemen just the tip of the iceberg.  The gut instinct, however, says that the question of a ceasefire is more one of when than if.  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
