 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - John Major scores own-goal for criticising lottery  grants</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>John Major scores own-goal for criticising lottery grants</b><br><br><br><b><h2>13 June  1996</h2></b><br><h2>No easy prizes in the obstacle race for funding </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Martin Wainwright</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Funding gay help groups with lottery money is an excellent subject for a public ding-dong, but the  Prime Minister's use of "ill-judged" is unlikely to be borne out by any examination of the application  process. To succeed in the obstacle race of a National Lottery Charities Board application - beating  odds of some 9-1 - an application must show more than ordinary merit and convince a succession of  generally cautious judges. Room for whimsy or political correctness is negligible in the basic marking  scheme, the product of much consultation with the voluntary and charitable sector, which provides the  initial league table.  <p>  <p>Applying groups must be financially sound and well-managed with relevant and thoroughly planned  projects, organised and properly staffed, cost-effective, designed to include regular monitoring of  progress and with a strategy ready for the day when the lottery grant runs out. They are then marked  systematically on relevance to the theme of each round (youth and low income in this week's grants,  health disability and care in the next), equal opportunities and the involvement of users.  <p>  <p>The application form provides the initial data. Next comes the detailed investigation by an  assessor, usually from the charity or social work field, and the rock on which the whole operation  stands.  <p>  <p>There are weaknesses in this rock: it is early days for effective moderation of those assessors who  tend to mark on either the high or low side; and the sheer weight of applications means some projects  are assessed by telephone rather than a visit. But every assessment I have seen is impressively long  and detailed; and each must go for further scrutiny by an NLCB grants officer at headquarters and - in  any large and most complicated or potentially controversial cases - for a second assessment by a  different assessor.  <p>  <p>And so, classified into a league table of merit, it reaches panels like mine, which are naturally  loath to muck about too much with the basic marking pattern. Among our highest-scoring projects this  time was the Bradford Lesbian and Gay Youth Project, whose &#163;16,884 was not singled out by John  Major. Rightly, because it had received the second-highest mark (equal) of all Yorkshire and  Humberside's 169 successful applicants. It was not agonised over by the panel. There would only have  been two reasons for rejecting it: a belief that gays should not receive lottery money, and fear of  headlines taking one small grant (0.13 per cent of the regional total of &#163;12,800,000) out of  context.  <p>  <p>The application went on for yet more checks: scrutiny by the England board member with an informal  brief to watchdog our region (Julia Kaufmann, director of BBC Children in Need), and final  consideration by the NLCB's England Committee which carries the official can.  <p>  <p>I understand the kneejerk reaction. Shock: Bradford gays win grant, North Yorkshire scout group  gets nil. But the situation looks different when you know that the gays scored 20 times higher than  those particular scouts. And another West Yorkshire gay and lesbian group failed in its bid, while  Bradford sea cadets got &#163;30,500.  <p>  <p>Martin Wainwright is chair of the Yorkshire and Humberside regional advisory panel of the National  Lottery Charities Board.  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
