 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Guernsey votes to legalise abortion</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Guernsey votes to legalise abortion</b><br><br><br><b><h2>18 June 1996</h2></b><br><h2>An island divided</h2><h3> Last week, Guernsey  voted to make abortion legal. End of story?  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Jonathan Rugman</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Many people on Guernsey are proud of their quaint island traditions; their manicured lawns, 35mph speed limit, low taxes, massed  churchgoing and the fact that you can't buy a drink or hire a video on Sundays. It is the kind of place where restaurants still call salt and  pepper 'condiments' and where a condom remains 'something for the weekend'. On the seafront there is a Morris Minor parked outside a sweet  shop, where a familiar Walls sign swings reassuringly in the breeze.  <p>  <p>But go inside and ask the customers about last week's decision to decriminalise abortion - the last part of the British Isles to do so -  and all agree that nothing has done more to shatter Guernsey's peace since the German Occupation itself.  <p>  <p>"I think they're a miserable bunch of sods," says one man, describing those deputies in the island's parliament who opposed the vote.  <p>  <p>"Who do the politicians think they are?" agrees the woman who runs the shop. "If you don't want the child, don't have it." But then an  older man explains that his half-sister was the product of a scandalous liaison with a German officer and that even during those dark wartime  days, there was no talk of abortion. "If a woman's pregnant, she's got to have it," he concludes. "The Guernseyman is a very reserved,  stubborn kind of local. We don't want your English ways." Last week's abortion debate was so fraught that priests were praying in the public  gallery before the 33-18 result in favour was announced. BBC Radio Guernsey mounted a rolling news service to keep pace with the  heart-searching. One deputy likened abortion to Hitler's final solution; when another wanted to describe the process of removing a foetus  from the womb, several others walked out.  <p>  <p>"I received so much hate mail that I dreaded the post coming," says Pat Mellor, one of those deputies who supported the motion. Another,  Mary Lowe, received a telephone call warning her that Guernsey's streets would be "strewn with blood". Feelings are still running so high  that normally law-abiding citizens have threatened not to pay their social insurance and health scheme contributions if the law is ratified.  <p>  <p>This is not the first time debate over women's rights has caused rancour. Statutory equal pay was debated and rejected in the Eighties.  "We were told to be patient, girls, your time will come," says Jean Pritchard, a senior parliamentarian and owner of a vegetarian cafe. In  1993 came a vote against a UN Convention on sexual equality, while three months ago a proposal for unpaid statutory maternity leave was  thrown out.  <p>  <p>"If you say you support women's rights, they think you're either a troublemaker or a Leftie," says Mary Lowe, pointing out that up to now,  at least 150 women a year have had to travel to the mainland for abortions. "All we are saying is that women should have the choice here  rather than exporting their problems." The new legislation permits abortion up to the 12th week where the mother's physical or mental health  is at risk, up to 24 weeks in cases of severe foetal abnormality, and without time limit to save the mother's life. Two of the island's 30 or  so doctors must give their permission.  <p>  <p>While the pro-choice lobby may have won the vote, however, the fight is far from over. Oliver Le Tessier, a deputy and Baptist Church  'elder', says he and his colleagues will now do what they can to ensure the bill is not ratified until after the next election, in nine  months' time. He hopes the new parliament will by then be so full of pro-lifers that abortion will never make it to the statute books.  <p>  <p>"People love this island and don't want it to go the way of the UK," Le Tessier says "Once a baby is born, I've never known it to be  unwanted. I've got many friends with disabled children and they are lovely." Le Tessier's objections extend from his conviction that abortion  is murder to his concern that if Guernsey legalises it, a whole host of unpleasantnesses - from euthanasia to road rage - will soon follow.  <p>  <p>Down the coast at the King's Centre, one of several evangelical churches on the island, the Reverend Jonathan le Tocq regrets the result  but says the debate has helped Guernsey's churchgoers focus on what their faith is all about. No one has left his 200-strong congregation  over the issue; if anything, his church has gained new followers. The Reverend is praying the law will never be ratified. "If a rapist feels  it's now easier for a woman to get an abortion, then maybe he won't mind what he does," he warns, recommending the "joy of adoption" rather  than termination as the way forward.  <p>  <p>Meanwhile, for Ruth (not her real name), who undertook a miserable trip to a Bournemouth clinic for her abortion 18 months ago, last  week's vote spells the beginning of the end of the attitude among Guernsey men that women are a sub-species who need to be protected from  themselves. "They don't realise how barbaric it is, having to fly to another country for an abortion, with none of your family around to  support you," she says.  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
