 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Family Law Bill </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Family Law Bill </b><br><br><br><b><h2>19 June 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Divorce rebels vow to fight on</h2>
<h3>  Baroness Young to lead diehards in battle for 'fault' statement after MPs endorse Family Law Bill   </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Rebecca Smithers</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The campaign by Tory diehards to wreck the Lord Chancellor's divorce reform bill refused to take no  for an answer yesterday.  Faced with a Commons third reading majority of 418 for the Family Law Bill, the diehards pledged to  fight on when the legislation makes its final appearance in the Lords.  <p>  <p>For those who have followed every twist and turn of Lord Mackay's controversial bill, the  determination expressed by former ministers like Baroness Young, John Patten and Edward Leigh, came as  no surprise. They had undermined the flagship of the Government's legislative programme with an  orchestrated campaign enthusiastically backed by the Daily Mail, triggering wider unease about  'anti-family' reforms which they feared would push up divorce rates.  <p>  <p>These fears surfaced again in the Commons on Monday night, when 20 ministers - including five  cabinet ministers - voted against a government-backed amendment to reduce the waiting period for  divorce from 21 months to 18 months.  <p>  <p>Labour wrenched a last-minute concession on pension splitting as the price for its support,  allowing the legislation to receive its third reading. Just minutes before the debate, Labour's legal  affairs spokesman, Paul Boateng, could be seen in intense negotiations with Gary Streeter, the  minister in the Lord Chancellor's Department. Mr Streeter only agreed to accept the change after Mr  Boateng dramatically threatened that there would be "no Family Law Bill" unless ministers caved in.  <p>  <p>The divorce reforms will come into force some time in 1998. They allow 'no fault' divorce after a  waiting period of 18 months - or 12 months in certain cases. Provisions strengthening protection for  victims of domestic violence are likely to be introduced sooner.  <p>  <p>The bill is expected to receive royal assent shortly after the Lords endorses the Commons  amendments - probably next Thursday - when there will be scope for some, albeit limited, change. The  reforms are designed to stem the rising tide of divorce in Britain, where on current trends one in  nine couples will divorce before their fifth wedding anniversary. England and Wales now have the  highest divorce rate in Europe - almost twice the average.  <p>  <p>Yesterday Baroness Young - the former Conservative leader of the Lords who spearheaded the earlier  Lords rebellion - was seeking government support for a statement that could be written on to a final  divorce notice, stating that a spouse was divorced against his or her will. Rebels failed to get  support for a religious beliefs clause which would have blocked divorce in certain cases where  ostracisation or hardship could be proved, but believe that the Government may back the idea of the  statement.  <p>  <p>She acknowledged there was no chance of forcing any significant changes and that the bill would go  through, but stressed her strong objection to scrapping the giving of reasons for ending marriage.  "It's quite wrong to abolish fault," she said. "We have undermined the status of marriage." Even  Tories were privately claiming that it was Labour that was clearly in control of the bill on Monday  night.  <p>  <p>Labour will continue its assault on the Government over certain aspects of the bill, including the  failure of ministers to provide any costings of the provision of free marriage counselling services.  <p>  <p>Yesterday the Lord Chancellor, Lord Mackay, insisted that the principles of the legislation had  survived. "The main structure of the bill is as it was," he told BBC Radio 4's 'Today' programme.  "The provision of a cooling-off period, its emphasis on trying to save saveable marriages with  mediation available, and much improved protection against domestic violence and in respect of the  matrimonial home - all of these are as the bill was."  <p>  <p>And the Social Security Secretary, Peter Lilley, sought to play down the significance of the  concession on pension splitting by claiming that the Government's acceptance of Labour's demand had  not changed its position. But the Law Society - which withdrew its support for the bill last month -  warned it would create a system that was "complex, lengthy, inflexible and uncertain". "Amendments  made during the final stages have not delivered any significant improvements," it said in a statement.  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
