 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Sadler's Wells theatre closes</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Sadler's Wells theatre closes</b><br><br><br><b><h2>25 June 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Last draught at  the Wells  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Judith Mackrell</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Sadler's Wells has always attracted a large and dedicated crowd of lobbyists who believe the  theatre should have been burnt down at birth. It's included all those who have shouldered painfully  through the Wells's crowded foyer to buy a ticket or a drink. It's included all those who've suffered  sciatica from sitting in the cramped auditorium. And it's been swelled by the snobs who regard EC1 as  just too long and undignified a trek from the West End.  <p>  <p>But the Wells - at least the current theatre - has always been more about gallant survival than  glamour. It has thrived on enthusiastic making-do. It was here that Lilian Baylis, the hockey mistress  of English theatre, chivvied our national opera and ballet companies through their formative years. It  was here that a depleted Sadler's Wells Ballet danced bravely as German bombs fell over Islington. It  was here that countless dance companies squeezed themselves on to a tiny stage, rehearsed in dingy  studios and shivered for lack of hot showers. It was here in all the Wells's various incarnations that  the neighbourhood has been entertained with an extraordinary range of goings-on. In recent years it's  seen male swans in AMP's gender-bending 'Swan Lake' and Michael Clark's bare bum. <p>  <p>In the early 19th  century, it saw mock water battles staged in a 90ft-long water tank, and in 1699, 16 years after  Richard Sadler first opened his small Musike House, it saw the Hibernian Cannibal eating a live  cockerel. So it was entirely fitting that the Wells's closing gala, 'Finale', was neither a grand nor a  glitzy affair. There were no dinner jackets to be seen except on stage, and though the star quotient  was high the emphasis was firmly on local talent - actors, singers and dancers who'd been most closely  associated with the theatre. The water in the titular well obviously possesses restorative powers  since the theatre's veterans seem to live astonishingly hearty lives. On Sunday night we saw  94-year-old Godfrey Kenton who spoke the first lines ever uttered on the current stage. There was Anna  Pollak, once principal singer with Sadler's Wells Opera, who is a mere slip at 81 and, of course,  Ninette de Valois, founder of the Royal Ballet, who was 98 this month and got a standing ovation from  her seat in the stalls.  <p>  <p>Unfortunately De Valois's own legacy was thinly represented at the 'Finale', since both the Royal  Ballet and Birmingham Royal Ballet were touring abroad. This must be the first dance and opera gala  without a tutu or a triple pirouette in sight. But since the tone of the evening veered deliberately  towards the whacky it probably made better sense to have Wayne Sleep dancing Charlie Chaplin than  Darcey Bussell performing Aurora. It gave us a really enjoyable reminder, too, of just how sharp  Sleep's timing is and how witty a physical mimic he is. His ex-Royal Ballet colleagues Wayne Eagling  and Derek Deane also tapped through their comically po-faced double-act in the Popular Song from  Ashton's 'Facade'. Ironically, two of the starriest dancers in the rest of the dance programme, Marion  Tait and Roland Price, dressed up as tramps and sang a rather successful duet.  <p>  <p>Yet if the programme's emphasis was on opera, it was opera taking the night off. Peter Grimes may  have been premiered at the theatre, Sadler's Wells Opera may have performed a rich repertoire of Verdi  and Mozart, but the highlight of Sunday night was 'The Three Divas' singing a blissfully wicked parody  of the Three Tenors' theme tune. Rosemary Ashe, Anne Collins and Della Jones competed shamelessly with  each other for the big notes of Nessun Dorma, and in a perfect imitation of overwrought and overpaid  Pavarottian emotion, added a unison routine of brow-wiping, arm-waving and ponderously wobbling  jowels.  <p>  <p>Almost as wonderful was Donald MacIntyre's air-shattering rendition of 'The Calf Of Gold' from  Gounod's 'Faust'; a clutch of singers, including Richard Van Allen, singing light-opera arias; plus, to  remind us that the Wells was the birthplace of British panto, a line-up of seven transvestite  principal boys singing filthy lyrics to 'The Boys Of The Old Brigade'.  <p>  <p>The demolition squad arrives at Rosebery Avenue on 15 July, and in less than two years time we  should see a brand new theatre. Though there will be a community base in the Lilian Baylis auditorium,  the new Wells proper will be a startlingly less cosy affair than the old. Ian Albery, its chief  executive, has orchestrated plans for a 21st-century venue with computer-controlled lighting and stage  technology, and a capacity for multimedia displays both inside and on the facade. Not only will the  theatre be large and well-equipped enough to attract the world's most interesting companies back to  London - particularly those presenting dance - but, as Albery says, the only limits on a newly created  performance will be those of the artists' imaginations. How comfortably the commercial and artistic  policies of the new Wells will rub together hasn't much been discussed. But we still have nearly two  years to enjoy the unsullied prospect of its future plans and dreams.  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
