 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Men complain to Equal Opportunities Commission over barriers to  work </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Men complain to Equal Opportunities Commission over barriers to work </b><br><br><br><b><h2>25 June  1996</h2></b><br><h2>Men losing battle for lowly jobs  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Sarah Boseley</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>For the first time, more men than women complained about finding doors closed to them when they  went looking for work last year, the annual report of the Equal Opportunities Commission revealed  yesterday.  <p>  <p>But the doors men were pushing against were often those they would have shunned in the past. Those  in their 50s, made redundant from male-dominated industries like shipbuilding, manufacturing and  construction, are pursuing the low-paid, sometimes part-time jobs that used to be left to the women.  While women have, in small numbers, broken into such hard-hatted domains as the building industry and  the fire brigade, stereotyping persists in the realms of 'women's work'. Jobless males are not  generally the preferred candidates in the retail, tourism and catering trades - let alone nursing and  secretarial work.  <p>  <p>Usama Tariq, now 18, applied for a job as an office junior with the Halifax-based textile  manufacturers, Samuel Lumb and Son, straight from school with a two-year course in keyboard skills and  business studies under his belt, as well as English and maths GCSEs. The letter invitation to an  interview was addressed to 'Miss Tariq'.  When he rang to confirm the date, Mr Tariq said that the interviewer was surprised. "He said they  were looking for a young female and it wouldn't be suitable for a male."  <p>  <p>The careers office, which had told him of the job, brought the case to the attention of the EOC.  Samuel Lumb paid Mr Tariq &#163;4,000 in settlement of his claim for sexual discrimination. "I think  it is a lot easier for women to get typing and clerical work," said Mr Tariq, now a part-time sales  assistant at Marks & Spencer.  <p>  <p>Vadivel Venkatasamy, a male nurse, who won &#163;2,500 from the Ministry of Defence in an  industrial tribunal case, was interviewed for a job as a staff nurse at Wellington barracks in London.  He was runner-up to a woman who then turned down the job, but the MoD failed to contact him in spite  of assurances that he was on the reserve list.  <p>  <p>Complaints from women still predominate in other areas - especially equal pay, maternity rights and  sexual harassment, said the report which noted a steady rise in complaints about pensions and  recruitment from men. Kamlesh Bahl, EOC chairwoman, said: "Stereotyped attitudes about the jobs men  and women can do still persist despite the changes in the workplace."   <p>  <p>*Don't put your daughter on the stage, Mrs Robinson. Your son, however, is a different matter. Actresses earn an average of 85 per  cent of men's pay in a year, and work 20 per cent longer, writes Dan Glaister.  <p>  <p>The report, Unequal Pay For Equal Parts, showed that a woman playing a lead role in the West End  earns an average of &#163;166 per day, compared with &#163;250 for a man.  <p>  <p>A spokesman for Equity said the report confirmed that the situation had not improved in the four  years since its last survey of pay. "We are going to go to the employers and say it's still bad and we  want to work with you to agree a joint programme to address the problem."  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
