 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Men complain to Equal Opportunities Commission over barriers to  work </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Men complain to Equal Opportunities Commission over barriers to work </b><br><br><br><b><h2>27 June  1996</h2></b><br><h2>Him indoors</h2><h3>Reports this week suggest that men are finding it harder  than ever to get jobs. For some, the solution is to stay at home   </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Yvonne Roberts</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>John Gullis is a Superman. According to Tracey, his wife, he has many strengths and only two  weaknesses: he doesn't know how to make money and he doesn't know how to look after it. A 'natural'  breadwinner he ain't, but John - a 45-year-old Essex builder reconstituted into a Surrey house-husband  - keeps his wife happy.  <p>  <p>Tracey Rogers works for a cosmetics company. She has a staff of 80, earns a salary "in the  stratosphere" and within a few weeks of having Tess, now seven months old, she found herself  "climbing the walls".  <p>  <p>John decided to take over. He finds the loneliness a problem, he misses "the crack" of being with  his mates and he objected to his wife's Christmas present - a saucepan - but he has no regrets. "If  Tracey is well-fed, well-slept and warm, if I can keep these balls juggling, she's happy," he says and  smiles.  <p>  <p>House-husbands sound as if they might be the pioneers of sexual politics - men who have eagerly  opted to take a slip road off the traditional route to masculinity. But what emerges when you talk to  couples in which a man has the main responsibility for the children isn't always a new and healthier  balance between work and family. Instead, it's often the repetition of the old dilemmas. Except, of  course, that the workaholic breadwinner and absentee parent is now the mother, while the undervalued  carer at home is Dad. Progress? Well, yes and no.  <p>  <p>Yvonne Berman, 39, is a barrister in industry who enjoys her job. She was "desperate" to resume her  career after a year at home with Jessica, who was unplanned. Her husband, Jonathan, also 39, was an  insurance lawyer and hated it. They disliked the idea of a childminder, so he took over as  house-husband.  <p>  <p>The knowledge that she is the single breadwinner, combined with the 12-hour days, exerts a strain,  Yvonne Berman says. "I worry that if I lose my job, we've nothing to fall back on. Then sometimes I  feel, this isn't fair. Women don't do this sort of thing, they are cared for... "  <p>  <p>Now Jessica is almost five and at school, Jonathan is developing a business from home. He is, says  his wife, "an ebullient personality". While some house-husbands are isolated, Jonathan has become one  of the 'mothers' who meet and occasionally complain because partners fail to appreciate just how much  they do, at home all day.  <p>  <p>"To my shame, I did begin to undervalue Jonathan's contribution," Yvonne Berman admits. "I'd  forgotten what it was like to be in the house. We went through a rough patch. It was the separateness  of it all. He had his day, I had mine. Now we try to intermesh our lives. I told myself, sod it, we're  getting into a terrible twist about something which is quite basic. We've got to raise our daughter,  earn enough money and make our relationship work. The rest can go hang."  <p>  <p>"If you're not honest," Jonathan Berman adds, "you can say being a house-husband works terribly  well. If you tell the truth, of course, there are tensions and resentments. It's impressive how much  dust women can see, where I see none...  <p>  <p>"Among the issues you have to face are which partner feels they have sacrificed more? What changes  occur when there is only one income, not two? It may be that men don't feel the same pull when they  come home and their child is in bed, while the idea of the husband as main earner is still more  acceptable. But I've no regrets. I have enjoyed being with Jessica enormously.  <p>  <p>"At some point," he concludes, "you realise that you may want everything but you can't have it.  Then you decide what you are prepared to forfeit. Nothing is perfect."  <p>  <p>Most men who find themselves house-husbands do not have the luxury of choice. According to a report  produced by the Equal Opportunities Commission this week, men are finding it increasingly difficult to  get jobs. With the decline of male-dominated heavy industry, more men than women are now complaining  about sex discrimination in job applications, with employers increasingly turning to women to fill  vacancies - 49 per cent of the workforce is now female.  <p>  <p>Given a choice, home is an increasingly attractive option. A recent MORI poll indicated that if  there were sufficient money, a staggering eight out of 10 men would stay at home. Another study  indicated that eight out of 10 women would choose to combine part-time work with family life. What  might go some way to meeting both aspirations, of course, would be more flexibility in the workplace.  Instead, we have almost none.  <p>  <p>Part-time work has no career structure; only 16 per cent of jobs offer flexi-time; British men have  the longest working week in the EU and career women are following the same route. A recent Institute  of Management survey demonstrated that working fathers increasingly resent the marginal role they have  in family life. Still, only two per cent of families, so far, have a man in charge of the children.  <p>  <p>In this shaky period of social transition, house-husbandry is not for the fainthearted. Having  accorded low status and no prestige to full-time domesticity, men who take up the role now find  themselves not only inhabiting an alien country of mother and toddler groups but competing in the  hitherto female domain of second-class citizenship.  <p>  <p>Traditional stereotypes have an alarming fortitude but this is because in some parts of the  country, they are reinforced by economic reality. Twelve million women work - but eight million are  part-time, their money used to 'top up' their husband's earnings.  <p>  <p>Gail, 39, married David Millard, 42, when she was 18. They have two children, 12 and 16. David was  a miner for over 20 years, then two years ago he was made redundant. He was at home until February,  while she continued to work part-time in a clothes factory. The Millards live in Doncaster, where 400  vacancies produce 4,000 applicants.  <p>  <p>"We were brought up on the idea that a husband goes to work, so it was sheer hell when he was  home," Gail Millard explains. "He did all the jobs all right but I felt less respect. I tried not to,  but it was there. His morale hit rock bottom.  <p>  <p>"We got through the bad time because we've always been a team, but the job has given him back his  self-esteem. A man at home, in my opinion, can lose his mind, literally."  <p>  <p>David is now paid &#163;93 a week as a full-time driver and labourer - but at least the status quo  is restored. Even with Family Credit, the Millards between them bring home only &#163;170 a week -  hardly resources that allow the luxury of 'choice'. They both work because they must.  <p>  <p>So what does make a happy house-husband? Philip Crayford shares four assets with John Gullis: their  wives' earning power; the knowledge that they have already proved their worth in the workplace; a  positive desire to be with their children; and a maturity that means they don't give a stuff what  others think.  <p>  <p>Philip, now 55, has two adult children from his first marriage. When they were young, he had three  jobs simultaneously (computers, building and heating), working "all the hours". Why? "To provide...  Now I understand far more what it must have been like for my wife at home."  <p>  <p>Ten years ago, he married Hazel Wright, 39. She is a solicitor, sits on a number of boards and is  passionate about her career. In the morning, she dresses the children, commutes for an hour to London  and may not return until 10 at night.  <p>  <p>Phil, 'The Majordomo', cares for Beatrice, five, and Tom, seven. He also has three weeks a year  alone in France. His wife, Philip acknowledges, has no time for herself.  <p>  <p>"Sometimes being at home can be rocky, sometimes it's fine, but we keep talking," he says  cheerfully. "On a Friday night when the kids yell 'Yippee, Mum's home' - well, that took a bit of  getting used to, but I wouldn't have it any other way."  <p>  <p>Hazel is equally positive. While she'd like a five-day weekend, she is that rare being, a happy  workaholic. "Women still hold the master plan. We can juggle 16 balls in the air, men are not going to  do it," she says. It's Hazel who remembers Beatrice's ballet shoes on a Tuesday.  <p>  <p>Who should stay at home? If money is no problem, common sense says the parent best suited to the  task. Better still is if both parents can play a role without being shadowed by stress or debts or  resentment about a forsaken career.  <p>  <p>Still, there remains that deep and primitive conviction that 'real' men earn money. Tracey Rogers  has an answer: "I believe men should be doing physical work. They should be tilling the soil or  building houses, this (house-husbandry) is a natural extension of that. There's something earthy about  looking after and protecting the family. I know I can protect myself economically but not physically.  That's what I want."  <p>  <p>It is Yvonne Berman, however, who perhaps touches on the most important question of all. "What I'd  like to know now is why have men put up with the stress of being the main breadwinner for so long  without trying to make changes?"  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
