 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Nelson Mandela visits Britain</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Nelson Mandela visits Britain</b><br><br><br><b><h2>12 July 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Celebrating in the royal box, thanks to the South Africans</h2><h3>Mandela Concert, Albert Hall  </h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Robin Denselow</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>It took a long time coming but there was celebration by the end. Just after 10 last night Nelson  Mandela was in the Royal Box at the Albert Hall, a slick figure in his black tunic shirt, dancing and  waving his fists to urge on the South African bands on stage. The Queen, at his side, looked a little  bemused but briefly clapped along.  <p>  <p>A state visit from Mandela without music would have been unthinkable, for his extraordinary history  both as prisoner and president has been chronicled and celebrated by some of the best political pop of  the past 20 years. So a concert there had to be, but one that would entertain the especially invited  audience that had been told the dress code was 'lounge suits or celebratory' and consisted of a brave  blend of politicians, community workers and anti-apartheid veterans, as well as the royal party and  the president. They were treated to a decidedly patchy show in which the British contingent came off  by far the worst.  <p>  <p>That was the fault of Phil Collins, who used the occasion for the first outing of his Big Band,  helped out with the requisite number of celebratory guests. Brilliant product placing, launching off  on a show like this, especially as it is to be televised, but the result was dire. There were 19 on  stage, most of them a German brass section, and they started by providing an unnecessary, raucous  big-band backing for their first guest, the South African trumpeter, Hugh Masekela. Then on came the  conductor, none other than the legendary producer, Quincy Jones. Even he could not improve the sound,  but he brought on an efficiently unremarkable new soul singer who is unlikely to repeat the success  Quincy enjoyed with Michael Jackson. Next came Tony Bennett, and by now it seemed that the Two Nations  celebrating were the US and South Africa.  <p>  <p>Phil Collins blasted back for Britain and made matters worse with a thin, indulgent set.  <p>  <p>The second half, dominated by South Africans, was thankfully very different. Ladysmith Black  Mambazo's harmony singing was stirring and reliable as ever as the leader, Joseph Shabalala, switched  from an appropriate new song about development and race harmony through to 'Homeless', which they  recorded with Paul Simon.  <p>  <p>Then came Bayete, a band from Soweto, who were the real stars of the night with their blend of  township styles, vocal harmonies and soul. Finally, the veteran Hugh Masekela was back again, this  time sounding far better with his own band in cool, stirring laments. By the time he had invited the  full cast to join the finale the audience were at last on their feet and the president was dancing.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
