 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - MPs vote to have 26per cent salary rise</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>MPs vote to have 26 per cent salary rise</b><br><br><br><b><h2>11 July 1996</h2></b><br><h2>MPs take the  cash  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Hencke</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>MPs last night rebelled against their party leaders and any notion of pay restraint by voting  themselves a huge 26 per cent salary rise by a majority of 125.  <p>  <p>Although all 126 members of the government payroll vote were supposed to turn out and vote for John  Major's recommendation of three per cent, 16 failed to do so.  <p>  <p>They included Cabinet ministers Michael Heseltine, Malcolm Rifkind, Michael Howard, Peter Lilley,  Sir Patrick Mayhew and William Hague - all of whom were described later as being away on valid  government business. The bulk of Tony Blair's shadow cabinet also either abstained or voted against  the three per cent pay increase - leaving Gordon Brown and his shadow treasury team, and the Chief Whip,  Donald Dewar, among the few supporters of wage restraint.  <p>  <p>Paddy Ashdown faced his own rebellion with 16 out of his 20-strong party opposing his line.  <p>  <p>The vote will transform MPs' pay levels into the next millenium by indexing their pay to senior  civil servants every year and guaranteeing an automatic review every three years, starting in 2000.  <p>  <p>It means an immediate backdated pay rise to 1 July of &#163;9,000 to &#163;43,000 a year for all  651 MPs. Cabinet ministers and junior ministers get a backdated rise worth nearly &#163;17,000 from 1  July, taking those in the Cabinet to &#163;86,991 a year and putting ministers of state on  &#163;74,125 a year and parliamentary under-secretaries on &#163;66,623 a year. Mr Major, who voted  for a three per cent increase, sees his salary rise from &#163;84,217 to &#163;101,557 with a guaranteed  increase after the election to &#163;143,000 for the new prime minister. Tony Blair's salary rises from &#163;65,992  to &#163;83,332 with the new Leader of the Opposition receiving &#163;98,000 after the next election.  <p>  <p>The MPs' 26 per cent increase was tempered by a large vote - 376 to 39 - cutting the top mileage  rate for MPs' cars from 74.1p to 47.2p a mile after widespread criticism because it encourages them to  set an environmentally bad example by buying large gas-guzzling Jaguars and BMWs.  <p>  <p>Only Nicholas Winterton, the Conservative MP for Macclesfield who drives a Range Rover, defended  the present system, claiming that the cuts could put MPs lives at risk by encouraging them to use less  safe cars. He was supported by 38 other MPs, mainly Tories.  <p>  <p>MPs also voted for an increase in their office accommodation allowance by a narrower majority of  26, backdating this to 1 April this year. The changes will also help the 100 MPs retiring at the  election by increasing their allowance to return to normal life.  <p>  <p>The votes came after a two hour debate in which only Chris Mullin, the Labour MP for Sunderland  South and Dale Campbell-Savours, Labour MP for Workington, argued for any restraint.  <p>  <p>The first vote was a crushing defeat, particularly for the Prime Minister, with MPs voting down by  317 to 168 the Government's recommended pay restraint package.  <p>  <p>On top of this, some 170 MPs either abstained or were absent, this rising to 200 when it came to  the crucial 26 per cent pay rise vote. Voting then was 279 in favour and 154 against.  <p>  <p>Alex Salmond, leader of the Scottish National Party, pointed out that the three main party leaders  had managed to assemble only 168 supporters in the first vote. "What test of moral authority is that?"  he asked. He added: "The Commons has made a major mistake tonight and have misjudged the mood of the  country."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
