 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Brutal murders of Lin Russell and daughter Megan in Kent</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Brutal murders of Lin Russell and daughter Megan in Kent</b><br><br><br><b><h2>13 July 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Cosy image shattered  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Alan Travis</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>Shortly before her death, Lin Russell wrote to a friend describing their daily route to school through the Kent countryside as "pretty and very English across fields and woods".  The killer who bludgeoned her and six-year-old Megan to death on that country bridlepath also shattered the cosy image that life is safer in England's small rural communities than in its inner cities.  <p>  <p>The idea that life is now more dangerous in the countryside is borne out by some crime figures - although murders, especially those involving children, remain a rare event.  <p>  <p>Home Office figures for England and Wales show that an average of only seven children a year have been murdered for the last 20 years. Until 10 years ago most crime was committed in big metropolitan areas, but during the 'crime explosion' of the late 1980s - when the number of recorded offences leapt from three million to five million a year - the situation was turned on its head as the 'lager lout' emerged at the centre of rural disturbances. In 1989, non-metropolitan police forces recorded more crime than their metropolitan colleagues. By last year the split had reached 56 per cent for shire forces and 44 per cent for city force areas.  <p>  <p>Home Office research also shows that since 1985 recorded crime has risen by an average of two per cent per year in metropolitan areas, but by six per cent in non-metropolitan areas. By 1993 people faced a greater risk of being mugged, raped or assaulted in Wiltshire and Cambridgeshire than in County Durham, South Wales or South Yorkshire.  <p>  <p>However, a recent study in Leicestershire found that for every burglary in a rural parish, the affluent suburbs of Leicester had four - while a high-crime council estate recorded 14 break-ins.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
