 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Orange parades given go-ahead in Belfast, leading to rioting  </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Orange parades given go-ahead in Belfast, leading to rioting </b><br><br><br><b><h2>16 July  1996</h2></b><br><h2>Riots "defeat for peace" admits PM  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Michael White</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>John Major acknowledged last night the violence which erupted after the fiasco of the Drumcree  Orange parade march had been "a defeat for the peace process". But in an interview with BBC's 'Panorama'  he said a lasting settlement in the province would not be "torn up and thrown away" by the street  confrontations.  <p>  <p>Relations between London and Dublin remained severely strained, however, with both Mr Major and the  Irish prime minister, John Bruton, reiterating their different interpretations of the RUC's decision  to allow the loyalists to march down a Catholic street.  <p>  <p>In the House of Commons, the Northern Ireland Secretary, Sir Patrick Mayhew, conceded the province  had suffered its "worst setback for many years", due to the violence arising from last week's  Portadown clashes.  <p>  <p>Launching a damage limitation exercise, Sir Patrick repeatedly defended the crucial decision by the  Chief Constable of Northern Ireland, Sir Hugh Annesley, to reverse his earlier decision not to let  Orange Order marchers enter the mainly Catholic Garvaghy Road.  <p>  <p>He announced a wide-ranging review of future management of 'controversial parades' as well as a  special inter-governmental conference under the terms of the Anglo-Irish Agreement on Thursday, at  which Sir Hugh will explain his tactics.  <p>  <p>On 'Panaroma' Sir Hugh said he believed that paramilitary influences on both sides of the sectarian  divide had deliberately created a crisis at Drumcree and that people would have been killed if he had  insisted that the march should not go ahead.  <p>  <p>With both the Social and Democratic Labour Party and the Democratic Unionists absent from the House  yesterday, it fell to the Official Unionist leader, David Trimble, to voice the resentment and  suspicions of loyalists that the confrontation was engineered by nationalist forces - even as he  appealed to Protestant paramilitaries "to maintain their ceasefire whatever the circumstances".  <p>  <p>Sir Patrick, who echoed that plea, won ready support from Tory MPs for his insistence there had  been "no political interference" in Sir Hugh's operational decisions. But Labour's Northern Ireland  spokeswoman, Mo Mowlam, made veiled criticisms of the Government's failure to act sooner, and  explicitly criticised Unionist leaders - "constitutional politicians who had not encouraged their  followers to obey the law".  <p>  <p>At a press conference, Mr Trimble insisted their presence in Portadown had prevented the kind of  disturbances which occurred at Belfast and Londonderry.  <p>  <p>In a frank admission that law and order had been at risk, Sir Patrick told MPs that orders made to  prevent "serious organised disorder" had been overwhelmed by "a clear and reprehensible intention to  over-stretch the capacity of the RUC".  <p>  <p>At Drumcree, where Orange activists had been trying to break through, there had been "insidious,  despicable and disgusting threats" to families of RUC officers.  <p>  <p>Meanwhile, in Belfast, Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein president, called on London and Dublin to  reappraise the peace process urgently.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
