 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Ceasefire further threatened as 1,200lb bomb goes off in  Enniskilen, Co  Fermanagh </TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Ceasefire further threatened as 1,200lb bomb goes off in Enniskillen, Co  Fermanagh  </b><br><br><br><b><h2>15 July 1996</h2></b><br><h2>Ulster in turmoil: Guests tell of wedding that  nearly became a wake</h2>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Sharrock</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>The bride and groom were taking to the ballroom floor for the last dance when the warning call came  through to the front desk at 11.40pm. Martina McManus and Thaddeas Turbett, who had earlier exchanged  their vows, led their guests out of the Killyhevlin Hotel, still dressed in white wedding gown and  tails.  <p>  <p>Then the bomb exploded. "It was a most diabolical sound, almost like a flashing light and I just  ran away," Geraldine McManus, Martina's younger sister and bridesmaid, said yesterday. "I must have  blacked out because the next thing I remember is the hospital. "We were enjoying a wedding and it nearly turned into a wake."  <p>  <p>A second call had been taken by a priest in Enniskillen, acording to local reports. Whoever made the call claimed they were from the  IRA. The porter, Declan McGovern, had just brought the hotel's owner, Rodney Watson, back from the  town centre. They examined the four-wheel drive vehicle the bomb was in.  <p>  <p>"At first we didn't take it seriously," Mr McGovern said. "We went over to the jeep. I looked into  the back and just saw pieces of wood, and then I went round to the other side and put my head in  through the open window, when I heard tick-tock sounds. I shouted to the others, 'it's a bomb'." The  doorman, Willie Stinson, said: "We had all the guests out when somebody said there were people still  inside. I went back in with a policeman and we found a woman and child. Within two minutes of getting  everybody out there was a loud explosion."  <p>  <p>In the hotel car park, a crater 12ft across marked the spot where the grey Isuzu Trooper had been  abandoned by the bombers, primed with 1,200lb of home-made explosive. The car had been stolen 11 days  earlier in Dublin, suggesting that whoever was behind the attack was not waiting for Orange Week to  give a pretext.  <p>  <p>Sammy Foster, the chairman of Fermanagh district council and a leading member of the Ulster  Unionist Party, heard the explosion from his home, three-quarters of a mile away. He and his family  were also caught up in the Enniskillen Remembrance Sunday massacre nine years ago.  <p>  <p>"It was a sound like a door slamming shut," said Mr Foster, who nearly failed to regain the  chairmanship after taking part in a controversial Orange parade through the nationalist village of  Rosslea, in Co Fermanagh recently.  <p>  <p>"It's sickening to think what could have happened. In 1987 a bomb murdered 11 good people, and so  many were maimed and still are suffering," he said. A man aged in his 20s, and his wife and two young  daughters, came out of morning mass at St Michael's. "I don't think it was quite unexpected in the  atmosphere of last week," he said.  <p>  <p>"Most people will be saddened by it, especially here in Enniskillen, which is very mixed and both  sides get on very well together. There's no point asking why Enniskillen. Why anywhere?"  <p>  <p>Since 1987, the town has undergone a startling transformation. The main street pedestrianised, the  buildings cleaned, new shops and restaurants opened and the overbearing security restrictions lifted.  But nothing has been done to replace the building demolished by one of Northern Ireland's worst bombs.  <p>  <p>"After the events of last week we see the need to begin again," said the parish priest, Monsignor  Cahill. "It's just too bad that Enniskillen should be visited again by such a calamity."  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
