 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Diana withdraws from all but six charities as  patron</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Diana withdraws from all but six charities as patron</b><br><br><br><b><h2>17 July  1996</h2></b><br><h2>Charity begins at home as Diana cuts back</h2><h3> Princess withdraws support from 100  good causes, but remains patron of six groups</h3>  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>David Brindle</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>About 100 charities were yesterday dealt a blow bigger than anything the competition of the  National Lottery has thrown at them when the Princess of Wales resigned as their patron.  <p>  <p>Princess Diana, whose support has boosted the charities' fundraising by hundreds of thousands of  pounds, said she could not give the commitment they deserved as she sought to reorganise her life  after her divorce. Six charities are to keep the princess as their patron or president. They are  likely to benefit from the concentration of her charitable work on a handful of causes.  <p>  <p>Brian Roberts-Wray, chairman of the Institute of Charity Fundraising Managers, said: "The potential  positive effect for the half-dozen that she is staying with is probably substantially greater than the  potential negative effect for the 100 she is giving up."  <p>  <p>The princess's decision came in letters received by the 100 charities the day after her marriage to  the Prince of Wales was conditionally ended by a decree nisi.  <p>  <p>The letters said: "As I seek to reorganise my life, it will not be possible for me to provide you  with the level of commitment that I believe you deserve. I feel that someone else in the royal family  may now be better suited to support your tremendous endeavours."  <p>  <p>The princess's office put the number of charities involved at almost 100. A listing compiled two  years ago said she was patron or president of 115, suggesting she has resigned from 109, either  yesterday or previously. The six charities with which she is to continue are: the London homelessness  charity Centrepoint; English National Ballet; The Leprosy Mission; the National Aids Trust; and Great  Ormond Street children's hospital and the Royal Marsden cancer hospital, both in London.  <p>  <p>There was dismay among the rejected charities and, below the surface, resentment at the good  fortune of the six established, successful and largely metropolitan groups.  <p>  <p>One organisation in receipt of the dreaded letter was Ty Hafan, in Barry, South Glamorgan, which is  seeking to raise &#163;2m towards building the first children's hospice in South Wales. Last night it  wrote to the princess pleading with her to reconsider. Dominic Jenkins, its chief executive, said:  "The princess became our patron a only year ago, but our donations have increased dramatically."  <p>  <p>Vanessa Gould, spokeswoman for Turning Point, which works with people with drug, alcohol or mental  health problems, said the charity had been surprised to get a resignation letter.  <p>  <p>"She has said before that we are one of her favourite charities. Even as the letter arrived, our  chief executive was writing to her about some work which we thought she might do for us later in the  year." At one time, the princess was doing something for Turning Point every month, Ms Gould said.  "She did a premiere of the Apollo 13 film last year, which raised over &#163;60,000 for us."  <p>  <p>Relate, the marriage and relationship guidance charity, is another loser. It said the princess had  been "immensely supportive" since becoming patron in 1989.  <p>  <p>The charity has estimated that her presence at a film premiere boosted the money raised tenfold, to  &#163;100,000.  <p>  <p>The losses will not be merely financial. The princess has been able to focus attention on issues  not always easy to publicise. In 1989, she invited reporters and TV crews into her sitting-room at  Kensington Palace to meet youngsters with learning disabilities or mental handicap.  <p>  <p>Roger Singleton, senior director of Barnardo's, the charity involved on that occasion and another  of the unlucky 100, said yesterday: "The princess has often commanded mass attention when she speaks  out on issues which affect children."  <p>  <p>Mr Roberts-Wray said not all the 100 charities would suffer equally. Royal patrons were only really  effective if they were active and it was inconceivable that the princess had been truly active on each  organisation's behalf.  <p>  <p>One of the princess' closest friends said last night that she was depressed over her divorce and  wanted to wipe the slate clean.  <p>  <p>Rosa Monckton clearly speaking with the authority of the princess, told ITN: "It's not a decision  which she took lightly but clearly she does want to spend a lot of time with her children and planning  her life ahead."  <p>  <p><b>Royal works</b>  <p>  <p>Top Patrons* - number of charities  <p>The Queen - 215  <br>Prince of Wales - 160  <br>Queen Mother - 150  <br>Duke of Edinburgh - 140  <br>Princess of Wales - 115 (now 6)  <br>Princess Royal - 105  <br>Duke of York - 30  <br>Duchess of York - 25  <br>Prince Edward - 20  <p>    <p>* Patron or president, 1994  <br>Source: Charities Aid Foundation  <p>    <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT  BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0   SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
