 <HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Guardian Year - Labour launches five pledge Road to the Manifesto</TITLE></HEAD>  <body bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#ff0000" alink="#adeaea" vlink="#adeaea">  <A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/stitle.gif" ALIGN=right BORDER="0"></A>  <br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><blockquote><br><br> 
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Labour launches five pledge road to the manifesto</b><br><br><br><b><h2>19 July 1996</h2></b><br><h2> Labour's manifesto statement - Hard sell on the road to Downing St</h2><h3>Blair begins process of educating voters and stripping out the policies which may prove to be liabilities during his general election campaign  </h2>
  <br>By
<!--INFOLINE--><b>Michael White</b><br><br>      <p>  <p>When Tony Blair told party activists during yesterday's launch of Labour's Road to the Manifesto statement that if they "believe this is not the way forward, now is the time to say so", he sounded like an Anglican vicar asking the traditional question during the marriage service. Which is roughly where he finds himself as he embarks on a four-month campaign to woo and wed MPs, peers, the 350,000 members of the Labour Party, not forgetting those wary trade unions, and bind them in everlasting bliss to his distilled version of new Labour's priorities for government. What this is partly about is just that, locking in the activists to what Mr Blair hopes to do as prime minister, 'getting his betrayal in first' as cynics put it in tribute to the stormy Wilson-Callaghan years when charges of betrayal were leftwing coin of the realm.  <p>  <p>So the Road to the Manifesto is, in large measure, a huge education exercise, partly aimed at the watching electorate.  <p>  <p>But it also embodies a useful exercise in stripping down policy commitments, jettisoning those which might embarrass the leadership in the coming election battle, getting the 'ditching and dumping' over and done with. Hence last week's referendum row.  <p>  <p>The selling of the package started last night when Mr Blair engaged in a three-way tele-conference, fielding voters' questions in what is routinely billed as an inter-active session, itself reinforcing new Labour's aura of whitehot information technology. A party political broadcast took the message to TV viewers at home.  <p>  <p>The process will continue today when the Labour leader visits Heathrow to inspect the airport, meet the workers and then lunch in the British Airways boardroom. And by 4 o'clock he will be in Gloucester, accompanied by John Prescott, selling The Road to a mixed audience - tickets by application - and taking their questions.  <p>  <p>So it will be for Blair and his shadow allies throughout the summer months. There will be public meetings, union conferences, interviews and speeches, leading up to the party conference in Blackpool from 30 September, which is expected - emphatically - to endorse the statement.  <p>  <p>After that, in a repeat performance of the campaign to re-write Clause 4, every Labour Party member on the computerised list at party HQ in Walworth Road will be asked to vote yes or no on the document. The result will be known in late November or December.  <p>  <p>It all has the merit of keeping everyone busy and thus out of mischief. As one shadow minister said of the Clause 4 debate: "If it hadn't been for Clause 4 we'd have been facing demand for a minimum wage of &#163;12 an hour by now."  <p>  <p>Except that it is not quite like the 1994/95 Clause 4 battle. That may have been a top-down initiative too, but there were at least two sides to the argument: old Clause 4 versus its updated rival. Victory is all but assured in 1996, but this time there must be genuine fears that the turn-out will be low, either because Old Labourites quietly abstain or new supporters feel no need to endorse a foregone conclusion.  <p>  <p>Such an outcome would allow the Tories to revive claims that Blair leads an unreconstructed party. It might also vindicate complaints that the idea which Mr Blair sprung on his NEC on 27 March  - having decided how to proceed during his Christmas holidays in Australia - is all about marginalising the unions and local activists by appealing over their heads to the lay membership.  <p>  <p>In short, the smooth presentation of yesterday's statement should not obliterate entirely the fact that it remains yet another of Mr Blair's gambles on the Road to Downing Street.  <p>  <p>Blair opted for that gamble because he felt the Clause 4 exercise went well despite predictions of disaster. The tour he undertook at that time let him capitalise on his ability to be impressive on the stump.  <p>  <p>This is altogether a riskier project. In a recent after-dinner speech, Roy Jenkins likened Mr Blair's position to a man carrying a delicate Ming vase across a polished museum floor: one slip and it smashes.  <p>  <p>Yesterday, Mr Blair chose to highlight five policy priorities, all of them priorities in the public mind, according to the pollster Robert Worcester, speaking on Channel 4. If it succeeds he and his kitchen cabinet may highlight five more.  <p>  <p>But the Tory onslaught last night, though ham-fisted, signalled a determination to thwart the Labour leadership's efforts to turn its manifesto into the fiscal equivalent of an American Stealth bomber. John Major rattled off a list of implied tax increases, Kenneth Clarke took a dig at supposed errors in Labour's sums, and party chairman Brian Mawhinney came up with a sinister pair of eyes peeping from behind a 'New Labour, New Danger' poster. The ad will appear in Tory papers today. It will be much harder for the Tories to hit the target this time than in 1992 when Neil Kinnock's volatile personality and John Smith's shadow budget allowed Tory strategists to murmur 'tax and Kinnock' whenever they were asked how they were going to win against the odds.  <p>  <p>Far from having no policies, a repeated jibe, Labour has lots. Yesterday's statement is highly ambitious. If prime minister Blair fulfilled half of it a grateful electorate would be impressed.  <p>  <p>Yesterday, even allies did not get a chance to discuss the statement. There was no time for debate because the printers were waiting, potential rebels were told.  <p>  <p>  <p>  <p>WRITING ON THE WALL  <p>  <p>Number of times these words appear in the draft manifesto  <p>  <p>new 107  <p>  <p>change 36  <p>  <p>security/insecurity 20  <p>  <p>lead/leadership 18  <p>  <p>partner/partnership 14  <p>  <p>stake/stakeholder 8  <p>  <p>deal 8  <p>  <p>challenge 8  <p>  <p>tough 6  <p>  <p>socialism/socialist 1  <p>  <p>  <br><br><center><TABLE border=0><tr>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jan.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jandot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/feb.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/febdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/mar.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/mardot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/apr.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/aprdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/may.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/maydot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jun.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/jundot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/jul.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/juldot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/aug.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/augdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/sep.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/sepdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/oct.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/octdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/nov.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/novdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  <td width=40><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/dec.html"><IMG SRC="/g96/pix/decdot.gif" ALIGN=LEFT BORDER="0"></A></td>  </tr></TABLE></center><center><TABLE height=30 width=400 border=0><tr>  <td align=left valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/byauthor/autha.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/b2auth.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=center valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/index.html"><IMG border=0 SRC="/g96/pix/g96.gif"></A></h2></td>  <td align=right valign=middle width=200><h2><A HREF="/g96/bymonth/Obitjan.html"><IMG border=0  SRC="/g96/pix/b2obit.gif"></A></h2></td>  </tr></table></center></BODY></HTML> 
